commit_message:
Provide a quick way to run flake8

"run_tests.sh -p" always checks every file for errors even though you
have probably only changed a handful. This patch adds "run_tests.sh -8"
which only checks the files that were modified in the HEAD commit or
the current working tree.

It is borrowed from the recent nova commit b011325cc6.
The related ML post is:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/043346.html

Change-Id: If3c8e5e3e442257f796374edba02c3a23a85839e

commit_message:
Add support for configuring Neutron

To further the goals of moving all the revelant things into
os-cloud-config, add support for configuring Neutron with a
setup-neutron CLI provided for convience.

Change-Id: I42a5188415439c72bcfc0f0489c3c847b11efc38

commit_message:
Assign only one IP per node in admin network

Extra IPs are not necessary to ensure reliable
PXE installation. We simply need to add each
MAC to the Cobbler profile to ensure that the
correct profile is chosen.

Change-Id: I0deea1d88f8e99f7743fd3b2df01ebaa8c0d914e
Closes-Bug: #1269726

commit_message:
Fix collection order issues and unit test failures

A randomized PYTHONHASHSEED caused the glance API to return certain data
in a nondeterministic order, breaking some tests. This patch sorts the
returned data before testing against a pre-sorted expected values.

This patch also fixes some unit test failures with the new version of
testtools (0.9.36) and directly calling setUp(). This was added to this
patch to avoid blocking more Glance tests.

Co-authored-by: Fei Long Wang <flwang@catalyst.net.nz>
Co-authored-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

Partial-bug: #1348818

Change-Id: Ie92c6bb5663826713ca99e8f2f7d70f3faef6675

commit_message:
lockutils: catch BusyError when locking with timeout

If the IPC lock is used with a timeout value, an error can be raised. So
we need to catch it and convert it to a correct return value.

Change-Id: I7dbbf466905da3c6a1c7813f18fd3e9eb5ad2b47

commit_message:
Add network's status check after creation of network

Add assert for network status should be active

As per my understanding when we are creating network,
we can not say that we have created the same ..
till the point network is not ACTIVE and cannot be used.
And logically also , it should be like this only.
Keeping all this things in mind proposed the patch for the same.

Change-Id: Iceba14dde08fa38f942190131b82b9ba515ed0d6

commit_message:
Added trove backup via horizon

The trove chapter in the user guide did not have
a section on how to use horizon to backup
and restore a database instance.

This commit covers how to backup and restore
a db instance using horizon.

This commit is a partial implementation of the
blueprint.

Change-Id: Iceb7a2e62c633d6f59d9d89aa6ae8ce30e354068

commit_message:
Moving network_id_from_subnet_id to neutron client

Code for getting network_id from subnet_id is used in several resources.
So function network_id_from_subnet_id should be moved to neutron client
plugin, because it will allow to avoid strange references on
NetworkInterface resource.

Change-Id: I18dfb9a21fdca7a3d047c1cc2e8950bec9622d8c

commit_message:
Importing with_statement from __future__ is useless

Python 2.5 is not supported by Horizon and since Python 2.6, the
with_statement is enabled by default.

Change-Id: I0b5dc5d3c83c393b4f27ddc1bc1af392a498360c
Closes-Bug: #1360879

commit_message:
labs: reduce rm call verbosity

The verbose flag for one rm use was once useful for debugging, but now
just screws up the osbash.sh output. This patch removes the flag.

Change-Id: I4f91bdb1d4406f3fb03b6de43bdfc91ce6405043

John, 
In patch set 1, found the reason why install_barbican() didn't fail even though ERROR_ON_CLONE=True. In https://github.com/openstack-infra/config/blob/master/modules/openstack_project/files/jenkins_job_builder/config/solum.yaml, I have added barbican to $PROJECTS as a workaround until barbican gets into devstack.openstack-infra/devstack-gate iterates $PROJECTS and does git clone without checking ERROR_ON_CLONE flag.

We can solve this in 2 ways,

Option-1: Recommend devstack users of barbican to do this when copying lib/barbican to devstack/lib until it's merged into devstack.
sed -e 's/ERROR_ON_CLONE=True/ERROR_ON_CLONE=False/' -i /opt/stack/new/devstack-gate/devstack-vm-gate.sh

Option-2: Set ERROR_ON_CLONE=False in install_barbican() and install_barbicanclient()

Current patch implements Option-2 as this is very clean and simple (openstack/solum handles this issue in the same manner)."}, {'account_id': 7262, 'date': '2014-08-22 20:27:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-22 20:58:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Allow devstack to do git clone of barbican

Currently on F20 env when devstack tries to install barbican and
barbicanclient, it's failing as corresponding dir doesn't exist and
ERROR_ON_CLONE=True. As barbican is not part of devstack yet,
we don't expect this dir to be present in this case, we should
set ERROR_ON_CLONE=False to allow devstack to do git clone.

Related-Bug: #1353696
Change-Id: I3c362f1b2e6c9abf940ea68a12085dd747ede37c

This will work if all you want to use addresses on the control plane (undercloud network) to access the VNC console.

But I don't think it works if you want to provide VNC access in a public cloud. When we recently refactored the tripleo-image-elements in 1f9c1f7385d21de7d3a9f935a0e505c921ef6f12 the point was really for public access (i.e. provide end users access to it). Today we use the NeutronPublicInterfaceIP to configure the IP on our publicly facing CI overclouds. So perhaps we should refactor both the tripleo-heat-templates and tripleo-incubator scripts so that:

1) This works if NeutronPublicInterfaceIP isn't set. (i.e. internal clouds, or dev testing, etc).

2) This also works for public cloud access when NeutronPublicInterfaceIP is set.

Thanks for carrying on the effort here. Initially I intended to come back to this but got busy with other things..."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-23 18:51:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-06-20 14:30:15.000000000', 'message': 'Set vnc to use controller virtual_ip

The address for the vnc proxy is incorrectly configured in the nova
configuration file.
The correct ip address is the ip address of the controller node.
The address being configured is the ip address of the local compute node, as it is not set so it uses the default setting.

The nova image_element nova.conf already has:
  novncproxy_base_url=http://{{nova.public_ip}}:6080/vnc_auto.html
but nothing was setting nova.public_ip - until now
Closes-Bug: #1332554

Change-Id: I41214834511680170393dd4325b510f549373141
'}, {'created': '2014-07-09 12:50:02.000000000', 'message': 'Set vnc to use controller virtual_ip

The address for the vnc proxy is incorrectly configured in the nova
configuration file.
The correct IP address is the Public Virtual IP address of the

commit_message:
Set vnc to use controller virtual_ip

The address for the vnc proxy is incorrectly configured in the nova
configuration file.
The correct IP address is the Public Virtual IP address of the
controller node as created by:
    I9649ee74ebaf62b6b929b28243a07c789a08867c

The nova image_element nova.conf already has:
  novncproxy_base_url=http://{{nova.public_ip}}:6080/vnc_auto.html
but nothing was setting nova.public_ip - until now

Closes-Bug: #1332554
Change-Id: I41214834511680170393dd4325b510f549373141

commit_message:
Update doc theme for barbican-specs

Update the theme used in the barbican-specs documentation to the
latest from oslosphinx. This will help create a more common look
and feel throughout specs.openstack.org.

Change-Id: I29157520915b0952ec650dcfc389667ceaf9b88a

commit_message:
Make signal_transport a parameter

There may be times where an update needs to change this without changing
the template, such as when updates will be done by something other than
Heat (i.e. Ansible).

Change-Id: I89d1153acab697b64468f841b3f2d17c169da649

commit_message:
Add specific docs build option to tox

Add doc venv to align with other OpenStack projects (such as Keystone,
Heat and Nova) who are using 'docs' for their doc builds.

Change-Id: Ib26cdac7142e9ec9efc231a578c14bfc7936ae61

commit_message:
Sync requirements with global requirements

Sync requirements.txt and test-requirements from global
OpenStack requirements repository.

The oslo.db >= 0.4.0 is needed by the recent patch to fix
the testsuite (https://review.openstack.org/116192).

Change-Id: I429dee9caf8c32963da683d596e25b14f62f77ee

commit_message:
Flake8: Fix E126 and E127

Fix these issues and enable E126 and E127:
E126 continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 continuation line over-indented for visual indent

Also fix a few occurences in the touched files of:
E128 continuation line under-indented for visual indent
H405  multi line docstring summary not separated with an empty line

Partial-Bug: #1333290
Change-Id: If822401fc7e1db49d595a0736a0dff8e00dfd217

commit_message:
ML2 Type driver refactor part 1

This commit moves segment management from the ML2 plugin to
the type manager in preparation for dynamic segment support.

Partially implements: Blueprint ml2-type-driver-refactor

Change-Id: I068b82369250d115ef91680f19e733ed9aa4659b

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-13 11:28:41.000000000', 'message': "Reorder operations in create_vip

Previously VIP's port creation was moved outside the transaction
to avoid deadlocks. It leaded to small chance of VIP being fetched
by rpc code with port being still None.

In this patch reorders VIP association with the pool so it's done
only after port has been created.

This patch also leaves small possibility of uncaught exception in
case of pool being concurrently deleted in the process of VIP creation

Change-Id: I584558aecc92db4d19fb72b1d006868b840a4d8c
Closes-Bug: #1356227
"}, {'created': '2014-08-13 11:52:15.000000000', 'message': "Reorder operations in create_vip

Previously VIP's port creation was moved outside the transaction
to avoid deadlocks related to rpc calls. 
It leaded to small chance of VIP being fetched by rpc code with
port being still None.

In this patch reorders VIP association with the pool so it's done
only after port has been created.

This patch also leaves small possibility of uncaught exception in
case of pool being concurrently deleted in the process of VIP creation

Change-Id: I584558aecc92db4d19fb72b1d006868b840a4d8c
Closes-Bug: #1356227

commit_message:
Reorder operations in create_vip

Previously VIP's port creation was moved outside the transaction
to avoid deadlocks related to rpc calls.
It led to small chance of VIP being fetched by rpc code with
port being still None.

This patch reorders VIP association with the pool so it's done
only after port has been created.

This patch also leaves small possibility of uncaught exception in
case of pool being concurrently deleted in the process of VIP creation

Change-Id: I584558aecc92db4d19fb72b1d006868b840a4d8c
Closes-Bug: #1356227

commit_message:
Updated Module File Dependencies

Previously, the Modulefile did not include Keystone.
This would cause the module to not install all necessary
dependencies for Heat services.  This patch allows Heat to have
consistent dependencies with other OpenStack services.

Change-Id: I1e34f88701523971d093c621748e974ef30843c6

Hi Don Dugger.

Could you answer Phil's question please?"}, {'account_id': 1981, 'date': '2014-03-25 04:28:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Actually, Yunhong implemented the cache, I'll get him to comment on Phil's question."}, {'account_id': 1981, 'date': '2014-03-25 14:26:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I would still prefer to have Yunhong comment but, in the meantime, there's one major problem with this change.  How and when do you evict an entry from the global cache?  The trust status of a node can chenge (a trusted node can be rebooted to an untrusted state and vice versa) so, if you have a global cache you have to have some way to update the trust status of each node in the cache.

Note that a major benefit of the cache is that you fill the cache by making a single call to the attestation service asking for the status of 100 nodes rather than making a separate call for each node.  Turns out the overhead for asking for the status on 100 nodes is about the same as asking for 1 node so this is a major benefit, even if the cache is re-created for the next schedule request."}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-03-25 16:17:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I think we need consider several factor for the global cache:

a) The cost of synchronization. With global cache, each host_passes() checking on each filter need get synchronized.  Considering the big number of the host and each host check now need a file operation, and considering number of the filter instances that now has to be executed in sequence, it may have a big impact of the performance

b) The possibility that need to flush the cache. Please note that we will flush the full cache even if only some of the cache entry is invalidate, and the returned time stamp is not always up to date. So depends on the configuration of the attestation_auth_timeout, we may still need flush the cache frequently.


These are the consideration that we implement only local cache for each filter instance, instead of global cache. And I'm not sure if you have any performance estimation data with your changes?

Thanks
--jyh"}, {'account_id': 9101, 'date': '2014-03-31 01:19:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2014-03-31 15:40:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

The current status, with one cache per VM, does not scale well because we can schedule dozens or more VMs at one time.  In this scenario, we have to call out to verify all host's trusted level many times in quick succession.

Perhaps I don't understand... Why was the cache was implemented with a timeout of 60 seconds if it's only for a single VM being scheduled?  Is this in case other filters take longer than 60 seconds and therefore we have to re-verify the trusted state of hosts we haven't reported back on yet?  This would worry me as it's suggesting that the trusted state of a host is highly volatile and a previous response from the filter that a host is trusted may not be accurate in 60 seconds time.

I think we need a global cache of some form - even if it only lasts for 60 seconds - so that multiple calls to the filter can use the same information about the hosts trust status."}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2014-03-31 15:43:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

For some context, I was seeing the requests to the attestation service taking over two minutes; so scheduling multiple VMs would be a big bottleneck'}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-08-22 18:42:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi, Bob, sorry that I didn't notice your comments before.

For your "because we can schedule dozens or more VMs at one time", I think if all VMs are created at one time, the local cache should support it?

For the question of the 60 seconds. The 60 seconds is the minimum time that a host can be rebooted. The idea is, if a host is rebooted, it's status is not trusted anymore unless we re-verify with the attestation server.

I'm also quite surprised to the 2 minutes back-forth to the attestation server. It's a bit long than me. Can you share me the attestation server you are using?

I do agree that we can enhance the performance, and I will do more investigation on it.'}]

commit_message:
trusted_filter cache does not work

The cache in trusted_filter does not work because when a new
instance is scheduled each time, a new instance of TrustedFilter
is made, which creates it's own cache. So we need a global
cache instance used for all TrustedFilter instances.

Change-Id: I3ce33fef787f039f3c5fedef7e6362e8df3ee4c7
Closes-Bug: #1223450

commit_message:
Enable dib service for master, heat-slow

Enabling the dib (diskimage-builder) service only installs repos,
so it is safe to enable by default.

Related devstack change where the dib service is defined:
Ia911cdee86f5b2e2ba1557e5aa8bf392b92ef555

Change-Id: I608195b1c2f2ae098bec925f2061d5a61906a134

commit_message:
Change httpd Keystone log to keystone.log

The normal extension for log files is .log. Log rotation should
work because the extension is as expected.

Change-Id: Ia5e42ea9d953e8395b86ab58cdef6c2d852efc94
Related-Bug: #1359995

commit_message:
Create message variables for exceptions

Instead of inline messages, let's create variables instead, as
it's easier to find strings, and mark them for translation.

Change-Id: Ibbcfdbc59d12a0cb4af50f73043d3ff7f3c76f99

commit_message:
Add new library oslo.utils

Add the new library oslo.utils so projects can start adopting it.

In order to use oslo.utils in python-keystoneclient (and probably in
other clients), the requirement has to be in stable/havana otherwise
the check-tempest-dsvm-full-havana-* jobs fail with an error:

 'oslo.utils' is not a global requirement but it should be,something
 went wrong

Conflicts:

	global-requirements.txt

Closes-Bug: #1357652

Change-Id: I9e61adfac71f159e3a6aa77cbcbb26279dc42869
(cherry picked from commit 10d2dfd4511dd4c7ba9c50d302058c33d6b6b778)
(cherry picked from commit daef7ed90d043c918f4fe4c5b5ae606998bb3055)

I investigated the failure reason of NEC CI. NEC CI always fails only with this patch. It is because the 106299 introduces a minimum version check of dnsmasq. The patch requires dnamasq 2.63 at least. On the other hand, NEC CI is now run on Ubuntu 12.04 and the version of dnsmasq from Ubuntu 12.04 is 2.59.  As a result, dhcp-agent failed to start almost all fails (some API tests and scenario tests (the latter is run locally and the result is not voted). I am not sure Ubuntu 14.04 becomes one of the requirements of third party testing. If not, it is not fair to stop launching dhcp-agent when dnsmasq version check fails.

I think the possible solutions are:
- to disable related features which require features from dnsmasq 2.63 or newer rather than stopping dhcp-agent
- to upgrade NEC CI based on Ubuntu 14.04 (it may take some time though it can be done this week)
- (any other?)

At least, the commit message should have DocImpact and UpgradeImpact flag and mention that this patch introduces this kind of version check. It also affects existing deployments that dhcp-agent cannot run without introducing new version of dnsmasq.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-08-19 03:49:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7183, 'date': '2014-08-19 06:21:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Akihiro,

thanks for checking the CI error. We discussed this on IPv6 meeting and this mail thread http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-July/040952.html, and decided to not support dnsmasq < 2.63. 
You can also check the history of this review to get more information. I guess the best solution will be to get NEC CI fixed and add DocImpact and UpgradeImpact to commit message.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-08-19 07:43:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Thanks, I still have a concern with this approach.

Requiring dnsmasq >=2.63 means Neutron Juno no longer supports Ubuntu 12.04 LTS. It is not a developer topic and we should have an input from operators. Although IPv6 support is important, not all operators needs IPv6 support and we need to consider operators who want Neutron with IPv4 only on Ubuntu 12.04. What was discussed in IPv6 meeting? The pointers will be appreciated. I would like to raise this topic to not only dev ML but also operators list.

I believe it is not a topic specific to NEC CI. It is more general topic.'}, {'account_id': 7183, 'date': '2014-08-19 09:55:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Sorry I posted the wrong email archive link in my previous comment. here is the right one:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-July/041471.html

We got responses from RedHat and Suse distribution guys but didn't get response from ubuntu side. I guess it will be safer to check the operator list to confirm."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-08-19 10:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Support Stateful and Stateless DHCPv6 by dnsmasq

* This patch adds support for subnets created with 'ipv6_address_mode'
  set to 'dhcpv6-stateful' or 'dhcpv6-stateless' by dnsmasq.
* If no dnsmasq process for subnet's network is launched, Neutron
  will launch new dnsmasq process on subnet's dhcp port in 'qdhcp-'
  namespace. If previous dnsmasq process is already launched,
  restart dnsmasq with new configuration.
* Neutron will update dnsmasq process and restart it when subnet
  gets updated.
* This patch enforces the version check of dnsmasq. dhcp-agent will
  fail to start if version of dnsmasq<2.63.

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Blueprint dnsmasq-ipv6-dhcpv6-stateful
Blueprint dnsmasq-ipv6-dhcpv6-stateless

Change-Id: I30e9950bbc5a89f01ccb9c561471f155a9fd1d11

commit_message:
Set version to 0.5.1

pbr pre-versioning causes current sdist to have versions leading up to
0.4.1, but that is already released - we should be leading up to 0.5.1
on this branch.

commit_message:
Add dib-utils

This project was split off diskimage-builder to contain files used
by other projects too.  In order to add it as a dependency of those
projects, it needs to be here.

Change-Id: I4fc46f963c6e9819efe2a77b0610f59fd1174773

commit_message:
Backport v3 config_drive API unittest to v2 API

This patch adds some v3 config_drive API unittest into V2 API to improve
V2 API unittesting.

Change-Id: Idbe85edd44d99cfa05e16faf10d4ca11f367c892

commit_message:
Extending IBMNAS driver to support NFS based GPFS storage system

- Adds support for hardware platform "NAS based on IBM GPFS
  deployments".
- This will enable IBM GPFS-NFS based storage systems to be used
  as a backend in OpenStack environments.

Driver certification test results:
  https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1358590

DocImpact

Needs an update in ibmnas driver documentation as this change
proposes a new configuration option (ibmnas_platform_type)
to cinder.conf

Change-Id: I09098341ca1948775166883e9b2290061fa6ed37
Implements: blueprint add-gpfs-nas-to-ibmnas

commit_message:
Switch to oslo.i18n in our code

Note that gettextutils are still indirectly used by fileutils (through log).

Does this affect any using projects that need to now really ensure they use/pass/configure a lock_path that were not previously? Maybe a audit is useful?'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-08-22 17:52:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

This was the behavior prior to posix locks merging in https://github.com/openstack/oslo-incubator/commit/edce46cf5efd6d738d379205f9bf526a498845e3

I have to admit I didn't realize that happened so long ago, but IIRC no projects actually synced that change before the Icehouse release, so Icehouse to Juno upgrades should behave exactly the same.  There could theoretically be some CD impact, but only if you started deploying after that change merged to a project and didn't set a lock_path.  Otherwise you'll already have this configured correctly (or you were already broken :-).

Also, there aren't any changes in consuming projects needed for this.  It's purely a deployment impact, which we unfortunately can't fix on our end (well...there was some discussion of a few mildly insecure options, but I'm not sure anyone was comfortable with them)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-22 19:57:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Use file locks by default again

After a lot of discussion[1], it was decided that this is the
safest way forward.  In the future we can investigate alternative
locking methods, probably as opt-ins so we don't break any
existing consumers of these locks.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/043090.html

Change-Id: I49ff98abc395d3263d55aeff26081b462a8a294e
Partial-Bug: 1327946

commit_message:
Slow down Kombu reconnect attempts

For a rationale for this patch, see the discussion surrounding Bug

When reconnecting to a RabbitMQ cluster with mirrored queues in
use, the attempt to release the connection can hang "indefinitely"
somewhere deep down in Kombu.  Blocking the thread for a bit
prior to release seems to kludge around the problem where it is
otherwise reproduceable.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ic2ede3046709b831adf8204e4c909c589c1786c4
Partial-Bug: #856764

commit_message:
add deprecation note to middleware

we're migrating middleware to alternate libraries. this patch
marks oslo-incubator version as deprecated.

Change-Id: I2f754d8a3aa49a0ea6ddb4e5e161bebb82181017
Implements: blueprint graduate-oslo-middleware

commit_message:
Move fake_quotas and fake_get_quotas into a class

fake_quotas and fake_get_quotas are used in ExtendedQuotasTest only,
and this patch moves them into the class for cleanup.
In addition, this patch moves the mox settings into setUp() method
for the same purpose.

Change-Id: I9920d6207bb27537e6d4e738d69d59f7ed255240

commit_message:
Convert v3 server SchedulerHints plugin to v2.1

This patch converts v3 server SchedulerHints plugin to v2.1 and makes v2
unit tests share between v2 and v2.1.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Note- to make V2.1 SchedulerHints extension work in V3 framework,
an extra parameter (request body) is being passed in server_create
function of each extensions.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I8a0d50efcda6fcd12971a41505127de5987eec18

commit_message:
Refactor network topology JSONView class

This commit splits JSONView.get() method into submethods per resources.
It helps us when we add a config option to disable Router panel.

Unit tests for network topology JSONView is added to check the
refactoring doesn't introduce a regression.

Part of blueprint hide-router-panel-by-config
Change-Id: I859b8dd5fcdf86ddd25e91f8eba28ba6f4406a45

[{'created': '2014-08-22 19:33:07.000000000', 'message': "Remove explicit call of tearDown in test_hds_nfs

By recent update of testools, explicit calls of tearDown() in the unit test
causes an error and the tests fail. the tearDown() will automatically called
after the test, so we shouldn't call it.
This breaks the gate, so we should remove the call from test_hds_nfs.

Change-Id: Ia745f5129cb562f37f303bf0be804941fcf86024
"}]
commit_message:
Remove explicit call of tearDown in test_hds_nfs

By recent update of testools, explicit calls of tearDown() in the unit test
causes an error and the tests fail. the tearDown() will automatically called
after the test, so we shouldn't call it.
This breaks the gate, so we should remove the call from test_hds_nfs.

Change-Id: Ia745f5129cb562f37f303bf0be804941fcf86024

[{'created': '2014-08-22 17:54:42.000000000', 'message': "Fix duplicate teardown to allow tox upgrade

When trying to use tox 1.7.2 we run into a second
tearDown call being made in the test as opposed to
just using Super's version of it.

This removes that call and seems to get everything
working under tox 1.7.2

Change-Id: I0a2674b7c1ba9589cab5e3b76777fce23b6601ad
Partial-Bug: 1348818
"}]
commit_message:
Fix duplicate teardown to allow tox upgrade

When trying to use tox 1.7.2 we run into a second
tearDown call being made in the test as opposed to
just using Super's version of it.

This removes that call and seems to get everything
working under tox 1.7.2

Change-Id: I0a2674b7c1ba9589cab5e3b76777fce23b6601ad
Partial-Bug: 1348818

commit_message:
Remove test_db_archive_deleted_rows

* The test may trigger a bug, in several test execution order
  For instance it causes trouble with the neutron full jobs
* Does not really belongs to the simple_read_only group
* A better solution expected to arrive

Change-Id: Ia9e70bb40c2e3d246f446b5b131abd8e3520e5ee
Related-Url: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/db-purge-engine
Related-Bug: #1305892

If the VirtualBox guest-additions have to be downloaded from the
Internet (usually they are provided by VirtualBox or already on the
disk), osbash fails to find the ISO image immediately -- it needs to
be restarted for that.

With this patch, osbash will correctly detect a freshly downloaded ISO
image.

Change-Id: Id767525cb25a2953e32ca5cba95fedddcdab6a5e
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
'}]
commit_message:
labs: fix guest-additions download

If the VirtualBox guest-additions have to be downloaded from the
Internet (usually they are provided by VirtualBox or already on the
disk), osbash fails to find the ISO image immediately -- it needs to
be restarted for that.

With this patch, osbash will correctly detect a freshly downloaded ISO
image.

Change-Id: Id767525cb25a2953e32ca5cba95fedddcdab6a5e
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
labs: fix neutron locale

The neutron client fails with an "unsupported locale setting" message if
a locale is sent via ssh from the host computer to the node VM.

This changeset works around the problem by setting LC_ALL=C if the
problem is detected.

I don't think it is acceptable to disable firewalld on all developers machines, despite the speed implications. It will silently leave them vulnerable to the network. I certainly don't want devstack doing this on my laptop. Developers can choose what firewall setup to use and we should honour that in devstack.

We should solely disable it in the gate CI systems we use."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2014-08-13 12:14:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-13 12:15:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

That looks better now'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-13 12:29:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Hmm, actually no, that is still going to disable firewalld by default on machines where it is currently running. The default behaviour should be to use the current OS firewall setup without change.

ie you need a tri-state

 * LIBVIRT_USE_FIREWALLD unset -> restart firewalld if already running
 * LIBVIRT_USE_FIREWALLD=TRUE -> install & enable firewalld
 * LIBVIRT_USE_FIREWALLD=FALSE -> stop firewalld if running'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-13 13:21:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

A possible alternative way:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113884/'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-08-13 21:34:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

The devstack gate is meant to test devstack as developers use it.  Part of the frustration that we've seen in the past few cycles is due to the gate configuration drifting from the standard devstack configuration.  Therefore, we are taking a harder line on ensuring that devstack works as intended from scratch in as close to the default configuration as possible.  If devstack needs to modify the firewall configuration for openstack to work correctly, it should.  But we should not have a gate configuration where all of the "correct" options are set which differs from the default configuration which is known not to work (or work well).

I believe that using iptables instead of firewalld was an option; perhaps devstack could handle making that transition?

Regardless, Devstack does all kinds of horrible things to a machine in order for openstack to run.  I don't think any of them would be acceptable on a developer workstation; rather it should be run on a dedicated vm, or in an environment appropriately externally firewalled.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-13 21:34:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I think I'd rather see something simpler, just a FIREWALLD_DISABLE[0] or something that defaults to unset, and when True simply stops the firewalld service or removes it if there are things that might restart it later.

devstack-gate can set it True to get the benefit.

[0] I don't really care about the name but it should default to being unset and make sense when set...in my mind unset == False.

BTW, the changes to the prereq files don't change anything except cache the firewalld package on distros that wouldn't have it by default otherwise...why install it just to turn it off?"}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-13 21:40:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Upon further review...

tools/fixup_stuff.sh already turns off selinux enforcement for fedora systems, adding the removal/stoppage of firewalld there makes the best sense in my mind.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-13 22:08:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Daniel ; I hear your complaint that it shouldn't disable your specific firewall rules, but in reality devstack is taking over the host completely

additionally, firewalld is not part of the default f20 cloud image; it appears to be something extra added by the rax f20 image

there seems to be no benefit to workarounds a) outside devstack and b) that will be rarely used.

BTW, the change does appear to drop the run time from about 1hour to about 30 minutes; in-line with Ubuntu."}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-13 22:21:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-13 22:21:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Seriously no, just no. Disabling the firewall on a users machine is just not an acceptable thing todo, especially for a bug that is really not an issue for developers. Only the gate systems are majorly impacted by this, and the performance problem doesn't exist in newer versions of libvirt either."}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-14 09:42:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Daniel - I get where you're coming from that removing firewalld is bad, but several counter points:

- this is guarded as f20 only; when it comes time to switch to f21 it will use the status quo

- if firewalld is not removed/disabled by default, every developer is left to debug why tempest/vms are running so slowly -- how else do they know to turn on the magic flag?.  unless we do it by default (this change).  I *hate* spending hours debugging a problem, only to find it's a known issue and I just needed to turn this or that hidden knob 

- just before this we turn off selinux (one day I hope to get it on, lower priority than getting the job working) and then we proceed to destroy the system with pip.  devstack never agreed to keep your firewall for you, and given it destroys everything else, this is not out of character.

- out of 3 images (upstream, hp, rax), only rax has firewalld turned on.  it's not the common case.  the others boot with nothing

- as an end-user there is an argument that this should be fixed upstream.  you're upstream, so I defer to you on that :)"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-14 09:54:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> - this is guarded as f20 only; when it comes time to switch to f21 it will use the status quo

As someone running F20 it is of no consolation once you've exposed my machine countless malicious attackers on the network

> - if firewalld is not removed/disabled by default, every developer is left to debug
>  why tempest/vms are running so slowly -- how else do they know to turn on the magic
>  flag?.  unless we do it by default (this change).  I *hate* spending hours debugging
>  a problem, only to find it's a known issue and I just needed to turn this or that
>  hidden knob 

Out of the total number of people running devstack, I venture to suggest that the percentage
who also run tempest is in single figures. The severity of the problem of slow VMs under
tempest does not justify making *every* single developers' machines more insecure by disabling
their firewall.

> - just before this we turn off selinux (one day I hope to get it on, lower priority
> than getting the job working) and then we proceed to destroy the system with pip. 
> devstack never agreed to keep your firewall for you, and given it destroys everything
> else, this is not out of character.

Disabling SELinux is clearly not great but is a much less severe action than disabling
the firewall IMHO. Yes, devstack does a lot of changes to the make but I would not
characterize that as "destroying everything". After running devstack I expect that
the machine is broadly as functional as before, with the exception that more software
is running. Some things like apache / mysql have been screwed around with, but that is
far from destroying the machine.  I certainly do not expect that devstack opens up the
machine to network attacks on any listening services.

> - out of 3 images (upstream, hp, rax), only rax has firewalld turned on.  it's not
> the common case.  the others boot with nothing

What is in the cloud images doesn't concern me here as that is not what most
developers using devstack are running. Developers run devstack on laptops /
servers they own with a "standard" Fedora installation which absolutely
has firewalld as the default integral part of the OS.

> - as an end-user there is an argument that this should be fixed upstream. 
> you're upstream, so I defer to you on that :)

As I mentioned already this is already fixed upstream and in Fedora 21 and
in the virt-preview add-on repo for Fedora 20. It is too risky to include
the change in standard Fedora 20 repos.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-14 10:14:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> and in the virt-preview add-on repo for Fedora 20

Why don't we enable this repo?  is this unstable enough that it's going to cause more trouble than it's worth?  

seems by using this we could be shaking out problems before the fedoraX+1 release day and easing everyone's pain at transition time"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-14 10:21:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

The virt-preview repository is a rebuild of the packages from current rawhide with no QA testing applied. Stuff goes in there with little-to-no user testing. It is intended as a way for people who want to be able to test functionality from future Fedora without upgrading their entire distro to rawhide. It is not something you want to unconditionally enable because most OpenStack developers don't want to be used as guinea pigs for as yet untested libvirt/qemu packages - they just want to focus on getting their own OpenStack work right."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2014-08-14 10:38:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

FWIW - I fully agree with danpb on this - leaving users who run devstack with firewalld _removed_ by default is really not an acceptable way to deal with occasional gate failures. 

I cannot possibly see how this can be a prefered solution to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113884/

I will add a comment on there as well - but faced with these two choices - removing it in our CI vms only is by far more acceptable one, from the standpoint of devstack as a tool.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-14 15:14:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

Daniel, running DevStack on a machine you care about is not a supported configuration. As you have noted publicly a number of times it makes assumptions about what it can do to its host and does them.  Joshua Harlow has a radically different approach which should be friendlier to 'pet' systems.

> Out of the total number of people running devstack, I venture to suggest that the percentage who also run tempest is in single figures. The severity of the problem of slow VMs under tempest does not justify making *every* single developers' machines more insecure by disabling their firewall.

I'll suggest that the percentage of developers running DevStack on Fedora is smaller than you imagine. This is only a problem for devs running F20 on a machine that needs to protect itself from a hostile network without help.  firewalld may be that help, but then you are running an app on your firewall.  An app which itself takes great liberties with iptables directly.

Sadly, security and devstack do not belong in the same sentence.  I honestly hate that.  We do occasionally take steps to improve that situation.  But I assure you it will be a long time (possibly never) before I'll ever suggest that a DevStack build is the right model to secure OpenStack.  DevStack is a 20lb sledge hammer and security is finish nails.

> Developers run devstack on laptops / servers they own with a "standard" Fedora installation which absolutely has firewalld as the default integral part of the OS.

That sounds like what happens at your job, but I haven't seen that situation yet first hand.  Developers run DevStack in virtual machines, either locally on laptops/servers they own or in some cloud somewhere (including AWS).'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-14 15:23:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

There are certainly things devstack does to a system which are not nice, but it is the only supported option we have for openstack development whether or not it is intended for "pet" machines at all. This is not an argument for making devstack ever more hostile to people's machines. Also note that running with firewalld is an supported scenario in production deployments on Fedora & RHEL, so unconditionally disabling this means devs won't be exercising the codepath that real deployments will. So I really fail to see any credible justification for why this needs to be inflicted on every developer instead of simply temporarily disable in the gate CI config as proposed earlier.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-14 22:42:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-14 22:42:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

If someone feels strongly enough that their f20 devstack host needs some firewalling, they can do that outside firewalld.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-15 00:21:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

firewalld is a valid solution to use in production deployments of OpenStack on Fedora & RHEL and as such developers need to be able to use this scenario during development. Blocking use of devstack when firewalld is running prevents that, even if they don't care about the performance hit because they're not using tempest at all or have a newer libvirt installed.

How about at the end of running devstack, after we print out the address of horizon, we do this:

  if ...firewalld is running... and libvirt is less than 1.2.4...

     echo "WARNING: using firewalld in combination with libvirt < 1.2.4 has a major performance penalty on VM startup"
     echo "WARNING: recommend updating to newer libvirt or disabling firewalld as a workaround"
  fi

that will make it pretty obvious to developers without blocking valid usage scenarios for them'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-15 11:50:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

f20+default libvirt+firewalld is *not* a valid solution.  If it can't run tempest in under 2 hours by default -- out-of-the-box without touching anything -- it is just as broken as if it were segfaulting.   devstack can not default to a case where tempest takes more than two hours because you happen to never run it.  nobody reads warnings

nobody but me has seemed to notice this so it's a storm in a tea-cup anyway.  Or perhaps people tried fedora, their CI took 4 times as long as Ubuntu so they just said "fedora is crap" and moved on (who'd blame them)'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-15 11:57:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I've proposed a patch which adds a highly visible warning message here:

https://review.openstack.org/114513"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-15 12:10:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

> f20+default libvirt+firewalld is *not* a valid solution. If it can't
> run tempest in under 2 hours by default -- out-of-the-box without
> touching anything -- it is just as broken as if it were segfaulting.
> devstack can not default to a case where tempest takes more than two
> hours because you happen to never run it. nobody reads warnings
>
> nobody but me has seemed to notice this so it's a storm in a tea-cup
> anyway. Or perhaps people tried fedora, their CI took 4 times as long
> as Ubuntu so they just said "fedora is crap" and moved on (who'd blame them)

That no one has ever complained before suggests that in fact the performance
impact of firewalld is irrelevant for most people using devstack and thus has
no need to forcably disable its usage for them. Unless you're running tempest,
which few people do on a regular day-to-day basis, the peformance hit is not
a factor that impacts development at all. A warning message is perfectly
satisfactory to alert people to the potential problem - something devstack
already does in a number of other cases. Don't insult my intelligence by
claiming that people can't see / read such messages.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-15 19:22:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-15 19:22:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

This changes the default behaviour so I added a flag FORCE_F20_FIREWALLD for those who have the desire/need to leave firewalld in place. danpb, the response was (and is): DevStack is not in the business of configuring networking more than what is required for Nova-Net or Neutron.  We'll leave well enough alone except for addressing brokenness (this review) as needed.

Can you show me how to undo the network config effects of launching a server using either Nova-Network or Neutron?"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-20 16:13:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

> danpb, the response was (and is): DevStack is not in the business of configuring networking more than what is required for Nova-Net or Neutron. We'll leave well enough alone except for addressing brokenness (this review) as needed.

That doesn't make any sense at all. Throughout OpenStack there are a variety of underlying OS technologies that can be used in combination with the OpenStack layer and devstack has support for explicitly turning on/off these options. Supporting an explicit choice of iptables vs firewalld is no different to the countless other things devstack configures."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-20 16:40:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

When Docker was still supported we required them to do the basic Docker installation and configuration before stack.sh ran.  It was in a script in tools so it was in the repo, but otherwise DevStack stayed out of preparing the system.  OpenDaylight was in a similar situation, Kyle and I came up with a split that seems to have worked.  On the other hand, Ceph is completely installed from within lib/ceph when it is enabled.

As you can see, there isn't a lot of consistency in regard to extra-curricular services.  But there was a demand for all of them in one way or another.  I do not see any demand (before your request) for adding basic network firewall configuration to DevStack, nor do I see why it should be included.  If Nova-Net or Neutron needed it that would be different.  And if there was, it would be in an additional review anyway."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-08-22 19:10:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Remove firewalld on Fedora 20 by default

firewalld interacts badly with the libvirt on f20, causing slow-downs
so great that it can timeout the gate.

Developers who want to leave it enabled should set FORCE_FIREWALLD=True

Change-Id: I5252a12223a35f7fb7a4ac3c58aa4a3cd1bc4799

commit_message:
Fixes catalog URL formatting to never return None

The old behavior was to return None if the URL template was not a string
(or not string-like). This was a mistake because a None should never be
able to make its way into the catalog.

This is based off of an IRC discussion that spawned from:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/81528/4/keystone/catalog/backends/sql.py

Change-Id: I12b0362d3869a3ec8dc1a6fa34e934a221deecbc
Partial-bug: #1347862
(cherry picked from commit 8599aa5d8393e3217e04bd8fb4bca2b2eaa41a69)

[{'created': '2014-08-02 20:45:50.000000000', 'message': 'Updates keystone.catalog.core.format_url tests

Since the tests were unit tests I moved them into the new directory

commit_message:
Ignore broken endpoints in get_catalog

If an endpoint is created with a malformed URL then get_catalog would
throw a HTTP 500 error. With this change we ignore all malformed
endpoints.

Change-Id: Ibe9a8fa49f410f2a76a0df732247bd6813fc734b
Partial-bug: #1347862
(cherry picked from commit 8737b43d2cc9cbc1af1ea7a0fbff39f1b1c50747)

Easy way to insert an alarm for testing this with devstack:

# localrc.conf should have the following as one line:
enable_service ceilometer-acompute,ceilometer-acentral,ceilometer-collector,ceilometer-api

devstack> ceilometer resource_list
# ...
devstack> ceilometer alarm-threshold-create --name cpu_high --description 'instance running hot' --meter-name cpu --threshold 70.0 --comparison-operator gt --statistic avg --period 600 --evaluation-periods 3 --alarm-action 'log://' --query resource_id {{resource_id}} 

# just replace the {{resource_id}} with something from a devstack

commit_message:
Add the Alarm resource to telemetry

Alarm supports full CRUD with query string filters on list.
Alarm state can be retrieved and modified through available methods.
Alarm History sub-resource implementation to be implemented separately.

Change-Id: Iaa8751c33939ecb40a60b08fd184c60888c4c148

commit_message:
re-add hashseed to avoid gate error

there seems to be sporadic behaviour in docs tests due to WSME. this
patch adds back the hashseed to stabilise results until then.

Change-Id: I9039d7f253b94e215e8f60a2d5e380bcf41a9d75

commit_message:
Add content and ToC to Telemetry Admin guide

Add content to the section System architecture and Data collection
and add table of contents to Retrieving data and Alarming.

Implements: blueprint add-ceilometer-admin-guide-to-openstack-manuals
Change-Id: I56065c21d62e3477900981a4f37af0cc95fe64b9

commit_message:
Add Ceilometer Admin guide chapter to OS manuals

Add the chapter file and the corresponding entry in
bk_admin_guide_cloud.xml. for initializing the Telemtery chapter.
Also add the skeletons for the main sections. The content will be
added in dependent patch sets.

Implements: blueprint add-ceilometer-admin-guide-to-openstack-manuals
Change-Id: I99bd13faee0f92cd9688a180acbe10bb9d0a8f13

commit_message:
Fix cfn_helper test for random hash seed

test_cfn_helper.py has a part of code which enforces the order of packages
or services processes. But the order is non-deterministic.

Change-Id: I37c4abe697fb3391793ce74fc730b127e920710a
Closes-Bug: #1360212

"}, {'created': '2014-08-13 01:25:04.000000000', 'message': "Integrate OSprofiler and Cinder

*) Add osprofiler wsgi middleware
This middleware is used for 2 things:
1) It checks that person who want to trace is trusted and knows
secret HMAC key.
2) It start tracing in case of proper trace headers
and add first wsgi trace point, with info about HTTP request
*) Add initialization of osprofiler at start of serivce
Set's olso.messaging notifer instance (to send notifications to Ceilometer)

*) Fix fake notifier

NOTE to test this:

You should put to localrc:

  RECLONE=no

  CEILOMETER_NOTIFICATION_TOPICS=notifications,profiler

  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-acompute,ceilometer-acentral,ceilometer-anotification,ceilometer-collector
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-alarm-evaluator,ceilometer-alarm-notifier
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-api

You should use python-cinderclient with this patch:

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/103359/

Run any command with --profile SECRET_KEY

  $ cinder --profile SECRET_KEY create 1
  # it will print <Trace ID>

Get pretty HTML with traces:

  $ osprofiler trace show --html <Profile ID>

note that osprofiler should be run from admin user name & tenant.

commit_message:
Integrate OSprofiler and Cinder

*) Add osprofiler wsgi middleware
This middleware is used for 2 things:
1) It checks that person who want to trace is trusted and knows
secret HMAC key.
2) It start tracing in case of proper trace headers
and add first wsgi trace point, with info about HTTP request
*) Add initialization of osprofiler at start of serivce
Set's olso.messaging notifer instance (to send notifications to Ceilometer)

*) Fix fake notifier

NOTE to test this:

You should put to localrc:

  RECLONE=no

  CEILOMETER_NOTIFICATION_TOPICS=notifications,profiler

  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-acompute,ceilometer-acentral,ceilometer-anotification,ceilometer-collector
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-alarm-evaluator,ceilometer-alarm-notifier
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-api

You should use python-cinderclient with this patch:

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/103359/

Run any command with --profile SECRET_KEY

  $ cinder --profile SECRET_KEY create 1
  # it will print <Trace ID>

Get pretty HTML with traces:

  $ osprofiler trace show --html <Profile ID>

note that osprofiler should be run from admin user name & tenant.

Change-Id: Ic3ce587946eaa7e6b19cf35a2cc905ae5de29dd3

commit_message:
replace NovaException with VirtualInterfaceCreate when neutron fails

Currently NovaException is being raised by the _neutron_failed_callback()
and being treated in a try..except block that wraps the _crate_domain method.
The exception is too generic and will catch any exceptions, which are
subclasses of NovaException (for example: ObjectActionError),
making the domain variable not be defined and will mask the original exception.

Suggesting to raise and catch the VirtualInterfaceCreateException and
treat the domain destroy and cleanup with save_and_reraise_exception
in the except block.

Conflicts:
        nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

Related-Bug: #1337860

Change-Id: Ic972e286ded4e8b9d79ce1b0aa514bb4623d5f0b
(cherry picked from commit f0388d6fec0c4830c730af1adb3d02027eb2cd1d)

commit_message:
labs: wait for neutron to start

If we don't wait for neutron to start before creating networks, said
creation may fail.

Change-Id: I8d09a89d9f728f377987806d49eec37986641721
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
labs: wait for cinder to start

If we don't wait for cinder to start before trying to create a test
volume, we risk getting error messages back.

Change-Id: I554e97498bcc2ecbbd65ff19b798f8109a275357
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
Adds ability to add project name or id to VM names upon build time

Feature is most useful for flat networks where one may have several
projects/teams in one domain and hostnames are required to be unique
across the network or organisation. This will enable you to add
project_id and project_name to VMs by setting configuration variable
in nova.conf when using multi_instance_display_name_template,
for single instances you'd set single_instance_display_name_template
instead. multi_instance_display_name_template also has been amended
to be able to set project_id and/or project_name.

Added msg level LOG.exception(_LE())
Added and updated unittests

Change-Id: I08799ce330ae2133e666f166cd886d4cb45317d7

commit_message:
Silence urllib3 redundant logging.

This patch makes the default logging level of heat-keystone-setup-domain
to be WARNING and the 'urllib3.connectionpool' logging level to be
WARNING as well.

The intent is to remove unncecessary logging information from urllib3
library.

Closes-Bug: 1358093
Change-Id: I650e80aa1093c8c7e7c5dac3694d58139d2ec260

[{'created': '2014-08-22 17:22:03.000000000', 'message': 'Improve help strings

Make help strings consistent, following oslo.config recommendations:
* Capitalize properly

commit_message:
Split EC2 ID validator to validator per resource type.

Now there is only one method to validate EC2 id: validate_ec2_id().
It's used to validate both the Instance ID as well as Volume ID for
valid EC2 ID format. However exception class raised in both cases
is "InvalidInstanceIDMalformed" and EC2 error code is
InvalidInstanceID.Malformed.

This patch addresses this problem by adding two new methods:
* validate_instance_id()
* validate_volume_id()
These methods use validate_ec2_id() and raise appropriate
exception as well as appropriate EC2 error code based on
AWS EC2 Error Code documentation:
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/api-error-codes.html

Change-Id: I55591b8b643bb316e5001e645d71c13094106e96
Closes-Bug: #1199308

(2 comments)

Given functionality hides certain bugs due to missed verification stages:

 - at slave side:
   - verification while starting slave;
   - verification while stopping slave;

 - at master side:
   - slave attachment verification, see [1].

I would not suggest to merge code that hides potential bugs. And i'd like to see verifications becuase we can't guarantee that slave will start as quick as it's possible, there are possible delays in networking, VM delays due to resources load.


[1] On the master, you can check the status of connected slaves using
    SHOW PROCESSLIST to examine the list of running processes.
Link: http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/replication-administration-status.html"}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-07-18 14:43:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9782, 'date': '2014-07-18 16:03:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

It's an interesting point you raise, Denis, but not quite as simple as you think.  At slave start time, the SQL thread would be yes even in the face of a configuration error, and the IO thread could well be 'connecting'.  The real think to check is Last_IO_Error, but there's no way to know how long that could take, so we would have to poll.  While that would be somewhat useful, replication can in fact fail at any time for a variety of reasons, and that failure would not be detected.

The real solution, as originally outlined in the blueprint, is to have a mechanism that monitors the slave status and updates the slave site's heartbeat appropriately.  As this patchset only partially implements the blueprint, the heartbeat handling will be in a subsequent blueprint."}, {'account_id': 9782, 'date': '2014-07-18 16:04:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

s/subsequent blueprint/subsequent patchset/'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-07-18 17:57:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Yes, Last_OI_Error should be also taken into account.

I see next case:
I have a master instance and i want to attach replication slave to it. 
So, suppose i've got like X (where X is a size) data at master instance and slave would 
replicate all(or specific databases) data from master and for some reasons slave would not be able to start, 
but mysql is alive, so, how am i able to know if slave was started properly?

As i can see there's no mechanis provided to report about slave status 
(not taking into account guest heartbeat since you don't know what and how to report to).

So, for this patch, i suggest to add certain mechanis for reporting:
 - from slave site;
 - from master site.
 - from Trove site(this type of reporting is a combinition of [1] and [2]).


A bit more, given patchset missing exception handling at various stages. And, of course, low test coverage (units and ints).

So, the committer has to cover:
[1] exception handling at taskmanager site
[2] exception handling at guest site
[2.1] define and cover slave failure use cases
[2.2] define and cover master failure use cases
[3] design and implement pluggable reporting mechanism for
[3.1] slave
[3.2] master

Let's talk about time frames. 

Stages [1] - [2] (including [2.1]-[2.2]) should be accomplished asap, since J2 cut is too close.

Stage [3] (design part) can take awhile (agreed). But no longer than  Mid-cycle meetup +/- a week.

Stage [3] (implementation part, slave site) should be before finished before J3, we should have 3-5 weeks to review it.

Stage [3] (implementation part, master site) is easier than slave site, should be finished right after stages [1] - [2].


P.S.: I'm open for discussions and i can help with implementation.

In the end of all of these words don't get me wrong, i don't want to be a showstopper, but i also don't want to release something half-baked, something that works on honest words.


Best regards,
Denis M."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-19 19:18:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: -Verified

commit_message:
Mysql guest agent functionality for replication

Implement new strategy for replication
Implement replication strategy for mysql binlog replication.
Supporting methods in mysql service
Implement API methods in mysql manager
Define configuration settings for replication

Co-authored by: Nikhil Manchanda <SlickNik@gmail.com>
Co-authored by: Greg Lucas <glucas@tesora.com>

Partially implements: blueprint replication-v1
Change-Id: I70f0b5c37fe3c2d42426029bb627c141965eb524

commit_message:
Migrate test_snapshot_pattern to tempest client

Migrate the test and along with it migrate all the shared
functions used by the tests from OfficialClienTest to
ScenarioTest,create_server_snapshot()

Change-Id: I4d95cd02fcbbb62bb1631a38ee5d2c7e7d8f8d63

commit_message:
Check host is not none in each availability zone

Check that host is not none before trying to parse the services that
are up in each availability zone

Change-Id: I757f35ca2fa84da3441b544280c1c430bf3e8fb8
Closes-Bug: #1297920
(adopted from commit 7f30ab5124618c5b11eebf9c6d69bcfd8a47adc3,
change path from 'dashboards/admin/aggregate' to
'dashboards/admin/info')
Original fix by Santiago Baldassin <santiago.b.baldassin@intel.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-25 22:13:22.000000000', 'message': "Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but heat unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Change-Id: I2370759546adee7bf5e20fa214ed7fa1f31d6bfe
"}, {'created': '2014-07-29 16:31:59.000000000', 'message': "Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but heat unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but heat unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: I2370759546adee7bf5e20fa214ed7fa1f31d6bfe
(cherry picked from commit 47e4a7e12f2287cd938c652f56e96a108d59bfd5)

commit_message:
Use a singly created set while copying cookies

Previously a tuple was being created while iterating over each of the
arguments of a cookie for every cookie. This will prevent creating a tuple
that many times and uses a set to increase the performance of look-up using
`in`.

Change-Id: I10ffccae8eb3a9cb41b1045a08b891fed43efd99
Closes-Bug: 1359245

So this was bought up at the summit and there were three slides that prof. chadwick had up.

This is still the second option. Jamming all authentication through the plugins and having federated provides construct something that looks like a standard auth packet with methods: ['saml'] or ['federation'] 

There is really no point i can see in this. 

What i think would be better is for keystone to have a couple of stable interfaces through which a federated plugin could query a mapping and then create a token, on it's own, with all the same security checks we currently do, but without pretending that a user constructed a packet which has a methods: ['federation'] section.

How would you suggest handling a fallback to external if this code block is moved?"}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-08-22 13:11:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

Kristy,  good point.  I think we need to deprecate "external."  For your patch, just remove the catch block, and put in a comment that the auth method should be one of the expected methods like kerberos, x509, or saml.

I guess there is the corner case where "external" is in the body of the request, so we have to be able to deal with both its presence and absence.  However, I'd argue in those cases the existing code (with out the Pass) is the correct logic.

I think, for this patch, explicitly ignore the "external" method.  The only people using that do not need the mapping approach.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-08-22 13:13:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Standardizing the Federation Process

Split functionality for attribute extraction and mapping layer
for saml2 auth plugin. Renamed to mapped.py, leaving original file
for backwards compatibility.

Co-Authored-By: Guang Yee <guang.yee@hp.com>
Implements: bp generic-mapping-federation

Change-Id: If9a8cbf62334c796a70e939bf00e7b194e5749c8

commit_message:
Adds Hyper-V Compute Driver soft reboot implementation

Adds a soft reboot implementation for feature parity with other
Nova drivers as specified in the base virt driver's interface.

Co-Authored-By: Simona Iuliana Toader <itoader@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Change-Id: I963cbdacdfefca47d6e45fa0aafac188963bcaed
Implements: blueprint hyper-v-soft-reboot

commit_message:
Change type validate method of template resource

The type of template Resource property schema converted from parameter
is the same as input parameter type, including Number/String/Map/List.
Resource property schema type includes
Integer/String/Number/Boolean/Map/List. The Integer type is converted
from Number type, while Boolean type from String type.

Change-Id: Ic8ba281b5fb6e17a25fb8b5ba6a1102c827e42b9
Closes-Bug:#1317129

Although I donot know why the test only fails in this patch but, I think this is the reason why the test fails: https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-openstackclient/+bug/1353788'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-07 17:10:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

There are a couple of problems here:

* The handling of exclusive option pairs like enable/disable in this manner makes it impossible to detect when neither option is present on the command line.  It is why I want all of these to be changed to this pattern: https://github.com/openstack/python-openstackclient/blob/master/openstackclient/image/v1/image.py#L145

* test_endpoint_set_no_options() always succeeds because it doesn't test the actual results of take_action(), just that it was called.  It doesn't know if the early return happened or endpoints.update() was called.

* All of the remaining tests in TestEndpointSet class have --enabled or --disabled on the command line, so the default code path is never checked."}, {'account_id': 9101, 'date': '2014-08-12 03:37:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Patch Set 2 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-12 03:37:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Fixed resource errors logged at default log level

* Heat was logging resource failures traceback at default log level.

* Resources failing is a normal condition, and once a resource has failed,
heat has already reached one of the permissible state ex: CREATE_FAILED,
hence heat should not log the resource failures traceback in default log
level.

* Have made necessary changes to log resource failures traceback at INFO
level.

Change-Id: Ica27cac5a94734c2db08cee2e7fe31289169fec9
Closes-Bug: #1290565

commit_message:
Move CooldownMixin into separate file

CooldownMixin is a class that can be shared between OS and AWS
auto-scaling implementations.  This patch moves it to a shared
subdirectory.

Implements: partial-blueprint reorg-asg-code
Change-Id: I40e470460e84944d317f5b1772fc562abf62896d

commit_message:
Fix wrong log level

If a wrong key_name or image_name is configured in heat template,
"exception" log level is used to report it. This should be the "info"
level.

Change-Id: I79122c22f2278e7c1a4e3daba70c122b78fb9aec
Closes-Bug:#1353328

commit_message:
Include project ID in stack abandon data

This change adds stack project_id and stack_user_project_id to
the stack abandon data, so that stack-adopt can check if
the project_id provided in abandon data matches the tenant_id
of the current user.

Change-Id: If98db0a4a210965209d50f1b04208677f63c418d
Partial-Bug: #1301314

Enable lazy translation on heat

Enable lazy translation in heat/__init__.py so that heat
exception message can be actually handled and translated.

blueprint i18n-messages

[{'created': '2014-08-18 12:55:25.000000000', 'message': 'Move neutron_utils functions to neutron client

All uses of neuyron_utils functions have been migrated to using
the neutron client plugin version.

commit_message:
Using neutron utils function from neutron plugin

This patch replaces calls in resources and tests to use the client
plugin methods.

File neutron_utils.py was deleted as unnecessary.

Change-Id: If0db1da7079a9bfc3208ff1b209653d1dc7de01d

commit_message:
Move neutron_utils functions to neutron client

All uses of neutron_utils functions have been migrated to using
the neutron client plugin version.

Functions in neutron_utils are deprecated and will be deleted in the
next patch.

Change-Id: I1b00485bddffcb6b9dba2ac770668dde9d6a0d70

commit_message:
Providing reference on resource during preview

There are several resources which use physical_resource_name to provide
reference to itself. However these resources have no 'id' attribute
during preview process and returns None. This patch adds new function
physical_resource_name_or_FnGetRefId that calls FnGetRefId method of
Resource class if physical_resource_name is None.

Change-Id: I0e61743d5c105391eaec4c28150dddeee8a938bd

blueprint stack-snapshot

commit_message:
Add backward compatibility for notification_driver

Declare additional entry points for notification_driver option to avoid
breaking existing deployments that may use deprecated values.

Change-Id: I4f6abc33d01bb434d8ea9895aea2bfe6324049eb
Closes-Bug: #1355250

commit_message:
Removed undefined method in install_env.py file

There was a call from install_venv.py file to post_process method
of InstallVenv class, but this method is not defined in this class
as result it was raising an error. Even when this error doesn't
affect dependencies installation, it is not allowing to display user
information.

Change-Id: Idb77f164abee5625ac24800ddb94b9b8c0b85162
Closes-Bug: #1275025

commit_message:
Ensure PYTHONHASHSEED=0 for the 'all' tox env

This removes the setenv override and sets the required
PYTHONHASHSEED=0 for the 'all' tox target, which devstack-vm-gate.sh
ends up calling for the current Ironic job.

Change-Id: Icc6a1cae1e49140c4e4648f6c75ad415f92479ce
Closes-bug: #1359929

commit_message:
Updated keystone authenticate user_story

Took runs by changing public_workers parameter from 1 to 4 in
keytone configuration file, which increases parallelism.

Change-Id: I21315f0a56124642ac58c237e47db0b315d9e490

commit_message:
Add support for multiple environment files

This patch adds support for heat to accept multiple -e commandline
arguments. The environment files are merged, with newer values
overwriting older ones.

Change-Id: I01e2baf8dea3bafb1ac6eac34f281c5ff86bf4aa
Closes-Bug: 1350403

commit_message:
Fix fake_update in test_update_missing_server

In test_update_missing_server, fake_update should be used as update()
method but it is used as create() instead. In addition, the test comment
also is wrong.
This patch fixes them.

Change-Id: Ia4704413dd7355010546dba7096ed34225bb4b0f

commit_message:
Avoid extra lookups in extra-specs-list

extra-specs-list used to use the extra-specs cinder extension
to get information on volume type extra specs. This information
is publicly available through the volume-type API [1] thus we
can avoid the extra-lookups of querying the extra-specs extension.

As the extra-spec info is publicly available, remove the part of
the docstring of cinder extra-specs-list that says 'admin only'.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-block-storage/2.0/content/GET_getVolumeTypes__v2__tenant_id__types_Volume_Types.html

Change-Id: I9a8256a044511ac5233d8170fc57118ccaa1e217
Closes-Bug: 1343876

commit_message:
Cache snapshots in request for extension

The extended snapshots extension makes a separate db request for
snapshots which is horribly inefficent. In addition it causes an
issue when using all_tenants=1, because the second request doesn't
pass in the filter. Fix this by caching the snapshot in the request
object like we do for volumes and retrieve the cached object in the
extension.

Change-Id: Ia943438c8d48accb7f62c43f07642c3da2fe34ab
Resolves-bug: #1358960
(cherry picked from commit 4f0d1d36136bcb33f578b2999812f36cadd71cec)

Conflicts:
	cinder/api/contrib/extended_snapshot_attributes.py

Change-Id: Ia943438c8d48accb7f62c43f07642c3da2fe34ab

Or maybe I'm just reading too much into it, feel free to tell me I'm crazy and I'll +2 as well :)"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-08-22 21:35:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I've never seen greenthread spawning fail. It's all just a bunch of process-internal computation; it doesn't involve any IO or syscalls or anything.

Here's a small script I wrote to prove this:

    #!/usr/bin/env python
    from eventlet import GreenPool


    def func():
        return 1


    gp = GreenPool(size=10)

    # get any dynamic module imports out of the way
    gp.spawn(func)
    gp.waitall()

    print "Start"
    for _ in range(10):
        gp.spawn(func)
    gp.waitall()
    print "End"

When I run it under strace, I can see that the only thing happening between the print statements is some memory allocation:

    write(1, "Start\n", 6)                  = 6
    brk(0x2162000)                          = 0x2162000
    write(1, "End\n", 4)                    = 4

So, I guess spawning could fail if memory allocation failed, but given how Linux works, the kernel will just give you memory and OOM-kill you later when it feels memory pressure, so you really never have a chance to do anything about it.

tl;dr don't worry about spawn failing; it won't'}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2014-08-22 21:43:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Multithread optimization for object updater

This change makes the object updater work the same
as the container updater, which is that it now
spawns one thread for each node that it needs to
update. This should help optimize its
performance/efficiency.

Change-Id: If740b8c67c0d953e4b510913bd8594570d868da6

commit_message:
Fix expected error details from jsonschema

The jsonschema 2.4.0 release slightly changed some of the error messages
that are provided when validation fails. This updates the unit tests to
expect the proper string and avoid failing as a result.

Change-Id: Ic8e32140e49e394659e7ebbecb28afb704b23b7c
Closes-bug: #1358881

commit_message:
Update use cases to align with dev guide and positioning

This patch updates the language in the user guide to be more
consistent with our current positioning of Zaqar, and to
clarify some confusion around individual use cases.

Change-Id: I32d75b3d4bec6ad758ef27fc3b5daf32651b1a44

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-22 13:34:30.000000000', 'message': "Don't call config() in the global space

Calling `config` in the global space breaks the config generator.
There's another case like this in the wsgi transport but it's not loaded
as part of the config generation step.

Change-Id: If4bccf54e89994c665bb1d5f4f0766e7b7f16c6d
"}]
commit_message:
Don't call config() in the global space

Calling `config` in the global space breaks the config generator.
There's another case like this in the wsgi transport but it's not loaded
as part of the config generation step.

Change-Id: If4bccf54e89994c665bb1d5f4f0766e7b7f16c6d

commit_message:
Revert change to get_remote_client()

Changeset Idb4a1487d48af24ebcee8e7a78822b2858c1e90b added tempest
client support to the scenario manager and migrated some tests to
it.  It also modified the original OfficialClientTest's
get_remote_client() to use resource keys instead of attributes.
This breaks any test still dependent on the original functionality,
specifically test_baremetal_basic_ops.

Change-Id: Ie9b3f6ea4180d4206efb016563ca1c6d559ad8c4
Closes-bug: #1360367

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    and resubmit a new change-set.

commit_message:
Don't use swift roles when no swift

If openstack doesn't have Swift installation this role assign is
unnecessary and cause bugs and fails for other tests.

Change-Id: If3bbc49cde6144e883daaf77b8f551a0562c84c8

Cancel buttons on both the Create Backup dialog and the Restore Backup
dialog do not have borders. This patch fixes the problem.

Change-Id: Id86f599ce0fc852b0e73db82099b876a601ecb5f
Closes-Bug: #1359901

commit_message:
Fix bootstrap issues on Volume Backups dialogs

Cancel buttons on both the Create Backup dialog and the Restore Backup
dialog do not have borders. This patch fixes the problem.

Change-Id: Id86f599ce0fc852b0e73db82099b876a601ecb5f
Closes-Bug: #1359901

commit_message:
Fix IE spacing for pie charts

The svg pie charts are being mis-aligned in IE because ID doesnt
correctly process the height and width attributes on an svg element
Using a viewBox resolves the issue and doesnt appear to cause any
side effects in other browsers. Note that the IE charts will scale
slightly as the browser window changes. Chrome and FF do not
exhibit this because they strictly apply the height and width

Change-Id: Id45b1f11dd964425926795f6d07ab7bdc361f6ee
Closes-bug: 1342125

commit_message:
Fix class name for ServerGroupAffinityFilter

The class name for ServerGroupAffinityFilter is
ServerGroupAffinityFilter and not ServerGroupAntiAffinityFilter. The
wrong class lead to a wrong display on
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/devref/filter_scheduler.html

Change-Id: I690a60cb70eab4837544ddd0bff6f1264e639592
Closes-Bug: #1360375

commit_message:
Running without keystone v3 doesn't require uri_v3

uri_v3 is not required if api_v3 is false.

Change-Id: I5d63ca38b9f07ea07383472fb7fa82b369c72216
Closes-bug: #1295132

commit_message:
XenApi: Fix domu typo in neutron setup

A typo has been introduced during a previous refactor, leaving us with
two neutron config files, one with domu and one with domU extension.
This fix corrects the mistake, thus always the .domU file is used.

Change-Id: Iffb6e2f70915f50ee590c375494c6f642412b543

[{'created': '2014-08-13 16:21:36.000000000', 'message': 'Clean up local variable usage - Remainder

Minor cleanups in a couple ofplaces:
* Config funtions
* Stackforge
