commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but tempest unittests don't currently
pass a with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: Ib54364877a251db48c54dfdc43c503281ea1f04a
(cherry picked from commit 256a21de7681288231917a91232e2ae2cf1bf4d0)

commit_message:
Handle non-ascii characters in spawn exception msg

If a compute driver's spawn function returns an exception whose text
has any non-ascii characters (e.g., for globalization), the compute
manager's "reschedule logic" doesn't handle it properly as it runs
the text through the str() function, which causes UnicodeEncodeError
exceptions.

This simply sends the exception text through six.text_type so as to
no longer blow up and proceed with rescheduling as intended.

Closes-Bug: #1359427

Change-Id: I3fef783feffbe99c6971543c881e3fce2b60693b

functions used by the tests from OfficialClienTest to
ScenarioTest:

"l3-agent, dhcp-agent" is appropriate. This fixes it.

commit_message:
Fix typo in Table 1.3

l3-agent-dhcp-agent seems to be one agent, but indeed two agents.
"l3-agent, dhcp-agent" is appropriate. This fixes it.

Change-Id: Ie9f50fca865db9b33c419844b7ba28ee6a3fd673
Closes-Bug: #1360061

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but incubator unittests don't currently
pass with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: I8926ff3157f86ea2a28f558420dbb27f0a09746c
(cherry picked from commit ebbdcad9d23e6fd7e2e9328a0ef270f369a08c86)

commit_message:
Update revoke-ext

Update of the revocation events documentation to deprecate the use
of `expires_at` and add in use of `audit_id` and `audit_chain_id`.

Change-Id: I36ed24d08126ef2507af77ec6e65372cc07bbb2b

[{'created': '2014-08-12 09:05:25.000000000', 'message': 'Fix "NotFound" error in _clear_stacks()

_clear_stacks() will raise "NotFound" exception if stack was
deleted before wait its status. As stack delete is not a time
consuming operation, this patch fixes the problem by moving
the wait codes into same try block with deleting stack.

Change-Id: I29d4e443e5f355dbba188ccebe930f9401f3ccea
Closes-Bug: #1355666
'}, {'created': '2014-08-20 01:01:48.000000000', 'message': 'Fix "NotFound" error in _clear_stacks()

_clear_stacks() will raise "NotFound" exception if stack was
deleted before wait its status. This patch adds a try block
to fix the problem.

Change-Id: I29d4e443e5f355dbba188ccebe930f9401f3ccea
Closes-Bug: #1355666
'}]
commit_message:
Fix "NotFound" error in _clear_stacks()

_clear_stacks() will raise "NotFound" exception if stack was
deleted before wait its status. This patch adds a try block
to fix the problem.

Change-Id: I29d4e443e5f355dbba188ccebe930f9401f3ccea
Closes-Bug: #1355666

commit_message:
Move attribute dictionary to a dicts type

The attribute accessible dictionary subclass is
be better placed under the types folder under a new
dicts module (where any further dictionary like
subclasses can go).

Part of blueprint top-level-types

Change-Id: I7548773b3a0b0cd88e88b75228b6061404235af1

commit_message:
Use python abc in DeletableResource class

Fix pylint error about NotImplemented raised instead of
NotImplementedError.

Use the abc class instead of NotImplementedError.

Partial-Bug: #1346797

subject: Add attrdict to global requirements

To play devil's advocate, wouldn't it be better to be consistent with our code and use one access mechanism? preferably one that works with stdlib python? To me the difference between foo.bar and foo['bar'] is minimal.

That said attrdict is tiny, MIT licensed and supports all the required versions of python so I am not really opposed to this on any of those grounds."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-08-22 05:17:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hard to say, sometimes it's nicer just to access by attribute, taskflow isn't using this kind of concept in a ton of places (2 or three really), but it's convenient imho and a nice to have that may be useful for others."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-08-22 05:31:26.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

commit_message:
Add attrdict to global requirements

TaskFlow (and likely others) currently has code that allows
a object to be both a dictionary (accessed by key) and a object
that has attributes (accessed by attribute). To allow a nice
reduction of code it would be great to allow for usage of this
library which provides a equivalent object and type instead.

Change-Id: I8a864a4873f00ade4a99b7453598030ec20fd29a

commit_message:
Update param information on stack preview

A stack preview doesn't actually create any resources and so, the
'disable_rollback' param is not used at all.  This updates the info for
disable_rollback to make it clear it is there just for consistency with
stack create.

Change-Id: I013bbf64725de08a4062fe521252525d07d3bf04

commit_message:
Add wrapt for taskflow build

This change adds wrapt to the stable/icehouse requirements list
so the check-grenade-dsvm job, which tries to verify that the
requirements for the projects are correct across releases,
will allow the new taskflow to use wrapt as a runtime dependency.
Nothing else currently uses wrapt but taskflow will use it to
provide a correct and unified decorator for usage in its
deprecation module.

Change-Id: I5efdea41bcbe049a2a13742363d83e260f6b814c

This has potential to increase DB responses considerably when listing instances because of the join (it's almost better to just query individually -- for the same reason we query sys_meta separately). I'd prefer the fix to this NOT be to join. Plus, we only care about/use the fault info when an instance is in error or deleted states, it appears. This results in extra data returned from the DB for no reason. Combined with my first point, I really don't like this. :(

Is there not a reasonable way we can catch an InstanceNotFound and skip the instance?"}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-08-07 00:09:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Chris - not without really complicating the API layer code. 

Because it has to at various points handle that anything that can be lazy loaded may cause an InstanceNotFound exception, even though there have been pre-checks that the instance exists and the code has the instance object.

So we end up with situations where just before the data is being returned to the client we find we can't. Also more generally (and this patch does not fix this) by lazy loading information to be returned to the client we potentially return data about an instance which is an inconsistent snapshot because data is loaded into the object at different times"}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-08-07 00:14:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So if it is better to query separately, we could just force a load just after getting the instance. Because at that point we'll be able to easily and generically handle the InstanceNotFound exception. But perhaps that is something that could be done internally to the objects code with expected_attrs?

Note we do have this problem generically with server extensions - its a very very rare race but it can happen (its why pci_devices is already in expected_attrs for v3 because we happened to have a tempest test which would trigger it in the gate)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-12 22:10:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-08-13 01:18:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I talked to cyeoh about this and I think the better plan is to make sure that lazy-load operations always use read_deleted=yes. I'll put up a patch to do that tomorrow."}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2014-08-13 06:10:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hm, I don't like that as a long term plan... but maybe short term. IMO, our API should be able to handle races like this and detect 'oh the instance disappeared', and skip it from adding to a list and/or return 404 if it's a show."}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-08-13 07:49:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It's rather awkward having to handle an object which  can sort of "blow up" at any time though. Basically it means we'd need to sprinkle try/except clauses all over the place as we assemble the data in different places. Plugins for example can contribute additional entries to the output being sent to the user.

The ability to lazy load with read_deleted would quite neatly fix this problem. Note that with the exception of the fault information we do know before we retrieve the instance which attributes we need (it is dependent on which plugins are loaded). So it would be possible to set expected_attr in the general case to things we definitely know we'll need.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-08-13 17:44:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Chris, after talking about it with the other Chris, I think I'm leaning towards just handling this in the API. There are several reasons for this, but the most important IMHO is that we probably eventually want to get away from soft deleting things in our database altogether. If we do make lazy_load read deleted items now, then we'll just have to fix the actual code later once that's not a thing.

It seems to be (a naive occasional API hacker) that this should be trivial to handle in the API's infrastructure so that a 404 is returned in the specific case, and the instance is skipped in the general one. Can you explain why that's not the case so we can weigh the options?"}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-08-14 00:16:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Well to take one example, say a client requests using limit/marker and search options a list of 10 instances. So the API calls compute_api.get_all and we get our list of instance objects.

We iterate through the instances forming the basic responses and return it through the wsgi layer. The wsgi layer then calls out to the various plugins (one instance at a time) allowing it to augment the information returned (its not possible within a plugin to remove an instance from the list returned).

SO not only do we have multiple places we'll need to catch InstanceNotFound exceptions coming out from an instance object but we can get stuck in the situation where we have to remove instance information in wsgi code (which is not really meant to know about that sort of thing) but we're also potentially one or more instances short of how many requested. And its too late to call compute_api.get_all again to retry.

Note that we do know at request time which attributes we definitely need (with the exception of fault) because it is dependent on what plugins are loaded and we could query the plugins to find out what attributes they will use when we load them. I don't understand why specifying those attributes up front in expected_attrs is so much less efficient than lazy loading them when we will definitely be using them after every call."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-08-14 14:45:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It's not if we'll be using them, but I don't think fault is used during a normal instance list operation, is it?

I understand that the WSGI layer doesn't know about instances, but doesn't it know about iterating a list of things? Can't it try..except NotFound around each, remove it from the list, and then keep going? Should be a general solution whether we're iterating instances or flavors, no?"}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2014-08-14 16:20:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dan and I just looked at this a little more. First to answer your questions:  Asking for faults up front for an instance list is okay, as long as it doesn't result in a JOIN. Otherwise, there's a mysql response size explosion as instance data is duplicated for as many faults exist for an instance. And your patch here is actually mostly okay, since it is only querying for faults on a single Instance... but I'd still prefer we didn't query for it when not needed.

I didn't look closely enough before... and notice that the bug is only for a 'show' or 'update', etc. The InstanceList object's fill_faults() method actually works how we would want it to work. It queries faults for a list of instances but doesn't refresh the instances at all... So we don't get an InstanceNotFound on an 'index' or 'detail'.

However, when lazily touching .fault on an instance where it's not loaded for show/update, the real problem is that the Instance object wants to completely refresh itself. We should fix the object itself to not do this. Ie, rather than change the object to refresh itself with read_deleted='yes', we should just make a lazy load of 'fault' to only query and add fault to the Instance object without trying to refresh the whole object where it could have possibly disappeared.

So: I think Dan is going to work on a fix for the Instance object to address this."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-08-14 22:07:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yep, I did, and the other review how has that as its content: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113947/'}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-08-22 04:28:20.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Addressed by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113947/ instead'}]

With lazy loading of instance object data it is possible to get
part way through assembling data to return to the client when the
instance is deleted underneath it. This can result in the server
api request failing with an internal server error. To avoid this
we ensure we get the fault data which we may need when requesting

commit_message:
Fix instance object race in servers API

With lazy loading of instance object data it is possible to get
part way through assembling data to return to the client when the
instance is deleted underneath it. This can result in the server
api request failing with an internal server error. To avoid this
we ensure we get the fault data which we may need when requesting
the instance in the first place rather than relying on lazy
loading it.

Change-Id: I110a5e0d7a0d17c02d00607c7eabc0c8e09a0a41
Closes-Bug: #1352659

Installation of httpretty 0.8.3 fails in environments with LC_ALL=C
(e.g. from tox) with the following error: UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec
can't decode byte 0xc3 in position 133: ordinal not in range(128)

Change-Id: Ic0e0a37ef3c0994fa6cb4cb6b1b7f06700fcbf29
"}]
commit_message:
Avoid httpretty version 0.8.3

Installation of httpretty 0.8.3 fails in environments with LC_ALL=C
(e.g. from tox) with the following error: UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec
can't decode byte 0xc3 in position 133: ordinal not in range(128)

The patch puts problem version into black list.

Change-Id: Ic0e0a37ef3c0994fa6cb4cb6b1b7f06700fcbf29

'}, {'created': '2014-08-20 23:15:41.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes Hyper-V issue due to ML2 RPC versioning

The ML2 RPC version 1.1 breaks the hyper-v agent and

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V issue due to ML2 RPC versioning

The ML2 RPC version 1.1 breaks the hyper-v agent and
consequentially the RPC version in the Hyper-V agent needs
to be set to 1.1 to match the ML2 RPC base API version.

Change-Id: Idc4ae8d7dcff4331aca148a8f2a7a2b01679b3a8
Closes-Bug: #1353697

commit_message:
Send create.end notification even if instance is deleted

There was an unprotected instance.save() call which could raise an
exception and bypass a create.end notification.  This adds a try/except
block around that call with appropriate handling of the exception.

Change-Id: I308ee84f6ab2bb37ef6570ff896017615a5bf746
Closes-bug: #1358795

commit_message:
Add Spark integration test

This integration test includes spinning up a cluster, running an EDP
job, and deleting the cluster.  Cluster scaling is not included
currently.

The Spark example included is SparkPi.

Implements: blueprint edp-spark-integration-tests
Change-Id: I9cdb3ab29d3364024f5cbe42b3cf4bae398cd547

well hash_path doesn't strictly require a non-empty hash_suffix/prefix - that's more of a ring validation thing, which FakeRing doesn't seem to do.  Some of the tests set the common.utils constants in setUp, but it doesn't seem to be strictly required for FakeRing, and I think that's reasonable?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-07-09 19:00:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Well, what I don't want is for tests to fail if my hash prefix/suffix in my real swift.conf make a certain path hash to 0, but it hashes to a 1 in whatever Jenkins sets up.

If the real swift.conf doesn't leak into tests at all, then this is fine."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2014-07-09 19:41:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Remove fake _get_part and use the real thing

The get_part method is fast and stable given a consistent hash path
suffix/prefix, so there's no absolute requirement for the fake
implementation other than convenience.  OTOH, removing the fake
implementation and fixing the tests that were relying on it should make
it easier to write better tests going forward and harder to hide bugs
that don't show up when using the fakes.

There may be some overhead when writing new tests that use the ring if
you're making assertions on partitions or paths, but with a part power
of zero it's normally trivially obvious when a 1 needs to be a 0 or vice
versa.  Or you can just drop the assertions around the parts you were
faking anyway.

Change-Id: I8bfc388a04eff6491038991cdfd7686c9d961545

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-11 01:11:45.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the delete subcommand with a bogus argument

If someone runs "manila delete help", instead of the permissible
"manila help delete", the following happens:

ERROR: local variable 'share_ref' referenced before assignment

Normally we just let the exception fall through to the top level,
but the delete subcommand can have several arguments, so that would
go against what's apparently expected by the failure counting.
So, trap the problem, report, continue.

Since we're at it, made sure that errors go to stderr. In addition
to being generally correct, it's consistent with the existing code
in manilaclient/client.py:main().

Change-Id: Ib482fe8b29d3ab9f1af6a23b2ab54aea6e9e88bc
'}, {'created': '2014-08-13 21:30:46.000000000', 'message': "Print delete errors to stderr

Sending errors to stderr is just the right thing to do.
And, in addition, it's consistent with the existing code
in manilaclient/client.py:main().

Change-Id: Ib482fe8b29d3ab9f1af6a23b2ab54aea6e9e88bc
"}]
commit_message:
Print delete errors to stderr

Sending errors to stderr is just the right thing to do.
And, in addition, it's consistent with the existing code
in manilaclient/client.py:main().

Change-Id: Ib482fe8b29d3ab9f1af6a23b2ab54aea6e9e88bc

While this change appears to be (on the face of it) a valid change, there is a good chance that this is entirely unnecessary.

The underlying issue is that in cases where an exception is thrown and someone calls LOG.exception() which could cause a greenlet context switch, the exception state may be lost.

However, this underlying problem has been fixed in greenlet v0.4.1. 

There should be, therefore, no necessity to make this change at this point.

For more details refer https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1154140'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-08-21 10:39:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: -Code-Review

I'm changing my review comment from -1 to 0."}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-08-21 14:19:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I've confirmed that the greenlet change did in fact merge so this change should not be required.

Unless it can be shown for some reason that this change is required, I suggest that this not merge. See earlier comment for details about why."}, {'account_id': 7236, 'date': '2014-08-22 00:31:09.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
Fix unsaved exception in trove.taskmanager.models

When an exception occurs during exception handling, it loses the
information of the first exception.

For example, self.instance.volume_client.volumes.get() is called from
the inside of an exception handler and an exception may be generated.

We should use the excutils.save_and_reraise_exception() in this case.

Change-Id: Ic3fee35cc06653fbebfe3fb258a806c6646457af
Closes-Bug: #1297056

commit_message:
Addition of basic ansible install

This commit adds an element that can be used to install Ansible in a
disk image.  Presently the version is set to 1.7.0.

Change-Id: Ica6d582ba8fc9b998d4ba92eeab3d116af0d645b

commit_message:
Switch off caching to prevent cache poisoning by local attacker

suds package uses a well-known /tmp/suds directory by default to
store pickled objects. This could be subject to attacks. suds project
is un-maintained and some distros have a local patch that uses
mkdtemp() but still leak directories. It's best to remove the cache
completely. Note that if we really need, we could add a memory
based cached later. we should deal with this security issue first.

Closes-Bug: #1341954

Change-Id: Ieec9d99aa674adf5cbc9be924fef3856cf4e5d66

commit_message:
Adding Nova Client support for auto find host APIv3

Adding nova client functionality to use the auto find
destination host for evacuate.
This change makes the target host optional
on evacuate command.

Partial Implements: blueprint find-host-and-evacuate-instance

Change-Id: I40619b8d1eea6ae44ed5e43fb50ce2c1862686d6
Co-Authored-By: Juan M. Olle <juan.m.olle@intel.com>

commit_message:
Adding Nova Client support for auto find host APIv2

Adding nova client functionality to use the auto find
destination host for evacuate.
This change makes the target host optional
on evacuate command.

Partial Implements: blueprint find-host-and-evacuate-instance

Co-Authored-By: Leandro Costantino <leandro.i.costantino@intel.com>
Change-Id: I4e6b52df9c55b223c8693058d73125962cff4d16

commit_message:
Fix jsonschema>=2.4.0 message assertion

The jsonschema 2.4.0 release slightly changed some of the error messages
that are provided when validation fails. This patch updates the unit tests to
expect the proper string and avoid failing as a result by using regex
(.0)? instead of specific value.

Change-Id: Ifd41147fd6157038b102c78144d1f6cb16cc25e6
Closes-bug: #1359284

commit_message:
Adding target support for policy enforcement

Getting target data only from request context. No Db verification.
This approach is similar to how nova does.
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/api.py#L1826

Change-Id: I6aeef05e28d6ca2b11288bb2e61becabea97e76d
Blueprint: policy-target-support
Closes-Bug: #1291073

commit_message:
Restrict jsonschema to <2.4.0

There are incompartable changes in 2.4.0. E.g.:
https://github.com/Julian/jsonschema/commit/f13ac35b63d8b8a45c26419a85a5a7a8de156170

So we need either ">=2.4.0" or "<2.4.0".
Made "<2.4.0" as more safe. Will need to upgrade in the future.

Change-Id: Ic4ca84dddc6de7325ae0bc59c488546c381781a8
Related-Bug: #1359284

commit_message:
Revert test_rootwrap_filter to avoid python2.6 test failure

With oslo.rootwrap 1.3.0.0a1 which has a bug #1340792, that some filter
rules are dependent on its evaluation order, test_rootwrap_filter randomly
fail for a patch adding to etc/cinder/rootwrap.d/volume.filters with
python2.6, as evaluation order is randomly changes.

The bug in oslo.rootwrap is fixed in master branch, but is not yet
released and not available in CI. So this until new oslo.rootwrap is
released, this patch reverts the unit test to avoid to block reviews.

Change-Id: If86b6689ae36aa8810aad5b694ed43dfec1fd0c6

(09:36:36) flwang: mtreinish: btw, may I get your opinion on the image(glance) scenario test?
(09:36:51) mtreinish: adam_g: but when you add a setenv on a child job it overrides the base one
(09:37:19) suneelb left the room (quit: Quit: Leaving.).
(09:37:23) mtreinish: adam_g: so the actual fix is to drop the setenv there not to add the extra hashseed
(09:37:29) flwang: mtreinish: somebody said it's useless (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100140/), so I'm confused again for the policy what should be implemented in scenario test
(09:37:54) adam_g: mtreinish, ah, right.
(09:38:05) suneelb [~Adium@2001:4998:effd:600:99d6:6b7e:f4f0:41c9] entered the room.
(09:38:22) flwang: mtreinish: actually, my company is relaying on tempest as the gate if there is any change against our infrastructure
(09:39:07) flwang: mtreinish: and we are using scenario test as an important gate
flaper87|afk flwang 
(09:39:36) flwang: mtreinish: that's why we would like to see all the key components can be covered by scenarios test
(09:39:57) kmartin [kumartin@nat/hp/x-onbgmyegdxpcafuv] entered the room.
(09:40:35) flwang: mtreinish: besides, as a Glance core member, I do think those cases I implemented in this patch are reasonable. So I really need some advice about what's the thing I should do in scenario test
(09:40:41) mtreinish: flwang: ok, yeah so the line between a scenario and an api test can get blurry sometimes
(09:41:02) mtreinish: the rule of thumb is if you're testing a user workflow it makes a good scenario test
(09:41:21) flwang: mtreinish: yep, that's what I'm following
(09:41:23) mtreinish: what you're doing there is testing various aspects of the glance api and just putting them in a linear order
(09:41:43) krtaylor left the room (quit: Ping timeout: 240 seconds).
(09:41:44) flwang: mtreinish: wow  :(
(09:42:01) mtreinish: we have isolated test cases in the api tests for all of that already
(09:42:08) mtreinish: which i think was __afazekas point
(09:42:30) flwang: mtreinish: so you also agree it's not necessary, is it?
(09:42:47) mtreinish: flwang: yeah that's my gut feeling on it by taking a glance at the code"}]

[{'created': '2014-06-16 05:37:54.000000000', 'message': "Add scenario test for image service

As the key component of OpenStack, it would be great if Glance
can be covered by scenario test in Tempest. From the image
service perspective, below test cases should be included.

* create a new image without data
* list images to see if the new image is there or not
* upload image data against the new image
* create an instance and make sure it works
* create another tenant
* share the image with the 2nd tenant
* create an instance in the new tenant based on the image and make sure
  it works
* unshare the image
* make sure it's invisible from the new tenant
* make the image public
* ensure the public image can be seen and used from the 2nd tenant

Implement blueprint image-basic-ops

commit_message:
Add scenario test for image service

As the key component of OpenStack, it would be great if Glance
can be covered by scenario test in Tempest. From the image
service perspective, below test cases should be included.

* create a new image without data
* list images to see if the new image is there or not
* upload image data against the new image
* create an instance and make sure it works
* create another tenant
* share the image with the 2nd tenant
* create an instance in the new tenant based on the image and make sure
  it works
* unshare the image
* make sure it's invisible from the new tenant
* make the image public
* ensure the public image can be seen and used from the 2nd tenant

Change-Id: I34c3d227475d99d8295f89cd9bbb6f2c30dab173

commit_message:
Libvirt: Do not raise ENOENT exception

If the disk disappears during update_status(), only need to print
a warning, and do not need to raise an exception.

Change-Id: I87800c855c7b349f69163e33031404ad25e2a9ca
Closes-Bug: 1358609

commit_message:
Adds note for unexplained error messages

In the stable/icehouse branch for RHEL-based deployments,
it asked the user to start and enable dbus/messagebus. In
RHEL 7 this is not required as it's out of the box.

As Icehouse standardised on RHEL 6, we should keep it as
it is, but it's confusing if someone's deploying Icehouse
on RHEL 7 based platforms. This patch adds a note to advise.

References https://review.openstack.org/#/c/115753/

Change-Id: Ic16ff621b309aca270bca8bfe833553889a21c3d

Add a __init__.py file to test the v1, but do not test the hack of oslo
incubator.

commit_message:
Add a pformat() failure method and use it in the conductor

When the conductors engine raises a wrapped failure (which may
contain a single failure from a remote worker, or may contain many
failures if there were more than one such failures...) it is very
useful to show more than just the basic exception information (or at
least provide methods that can print out the information in a nice
manner).

This commit adds a pformat() failure method that formats the failure
in a nice and understandable manner and then uses it in the conductor
dispatching routine so that the conductors LOGs are much more useful.

Change-Id: I46afacf54c9b4cae885c76c09b51e61d71fe623a

commit_message:
Handle sqlalchemy connection strings with drivers

SqlAlchemy connection strings may specify a driver using the +foo suffix
syntax in the url scheme. Ceilometer should accomodate this type of
schema when looking up sqlalchemy drivers with the stevedore driver
manager.

Fix this by splitting connection string schemes on '+' and retrieving
only the first element in the resulting list. Doing the entrypoint
lookup on this element will preserve the existing behavior in loading
sqlalchemy drivers and should be a noop for other backend types.

Change-Id: Ieec5a4c47e8498a533d4e6954682a9bbe10bd4d9

commit_message:
Allow three periodic tasks to hit slave

Allows the following periodic tasks to hit a slave
if a slave_connection is configured:

_run_pending_deletes
_instance_usage_audit
_poll_volume_usage

Blueprint: juno-slaveification
Change-Id: I38585562e3d3579299e32b5f9ced9311f672abcc

commit_message:
VMWare Driver - Ignore datastore in maintenance mode

A datastore can be part of a datastore cluster. Any
datastore which is part of a cluster can be put in maintenance
mode. Instances cannot reside on a datastore if it is in
maintenance mode.
This fix ignores a datastore in the following scenarios
1. Stats update - Ignore a datastore during stats update.
2. Ignore a datastore during instance spawn.

Change-Id: Id0cb3f5fdb4d0bc4884cf5405fadc433d4a2b6ba
Closes-Bug: #1330065

commit_message:
Use oslo libraries - i18n and utils

Remove the files synced from oslo-incubator and adjust
the openstack-common.conf. Note that _message.Message extends
six.text_type so we don't need the extra condition check in
jsonutils.py. Tests have been updated to use the fixture in
i18n 0.2.0 to avoid directly referring to private modules.

Change-Id: I971df3a154317a5dff93c83143092c98023b84c9

commit_message:
Ensure ip6tables are used only if ipv6 is enabled in kernel

On systems where ipv6 module is not loaded in kernel we need to avoid
usage of ip6tables. This patch reads
/proc/sys/net/ipv6/conf/default/disable_ipv6 file and if ipv6 is
disabled then ip6tables are not used in IptablesManager

Closes-Bug: #1352893

Change-Id: I07e5851aa25eb98b7a97dff86b9850475df85f64

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-19 13:58:04.000000000', 'message': "Fix sporadic false failure in xprofile unit test code (master)

Same fix as is going through on feature/ec, fixed it there first
as it was happening often and no point in waiting until EC is
complete before getting it over to master...

Appears that what's been happening on feature/ec lately
with a middleware failure has to do with a hardcoded PID in
the test code itself causing a profile file to exist when
its not expected to by the test.

Test code used a PID of 135 and based on how get_logfiles()
is written, any real PID that starts with 135 will cause a
false failure in test_call().  This can be seen via inspection
and confirmed in logfiles where all captured assertions show
a profile filename beginning with 135.  Tried getting smarter
about choosing a fake PID (int) but then decided it was 100%
safe to use 'ABC' for this test since that'll never show up!

Change-Id: I958f1525c2727b3fb3f533242fa509fa8e59926c
"}]
commit_message:
Fix sporadic false failure in xprofile unit test code (master)

Same fix as is going through on feature/ec, fixed it there first
as it was happening often and no point in waiting until EC is
complete before getting it over to master...

Appears that what's been happening on feature/ec lately
with a middleware failure has to do with a hardcoded PID in
the test code itself causing a profile file to exist when
its not expected to by the test.

Test code used a PID of 135 and based on how get_logfiles()
is written, any real PID that starts with 135 will cause a
false failure in test_call().  This can be seen via inspection
and confirmed in logfiles where all captured assertions show
a profile filename beginning with 135.  Tried getting smarter
about choosing a fake PID (int) but then decided it was 100%
safe to use 'ABC' for this test since that'll never show up!

Change-Id: I958f1525c2727b3fb3f533242fa509fa8e59926c

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but incubator unittests don't currently
pass with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: I8926ff3157f86ea2a28f558420dbb27f0a09746c
(cherry picked from commit ebbdcad9d23e6fd7e2e9328a0ef270f369a08c86)

commit_message:
Add get_non_innodb_tables() to utils

Add a helper function to utils for detection of tables which aren't
using InnoDB storage engine in MySQL (something we want to enforce in
consuming projects).

Change-Id: I22889e23b025fc32fe76e4086cd3cd3d5bd0b771

commit_message:
Add notifications for policy, region, service and endpoint.

The endpoint policy extension will need to ensure stale
associations are removed on deletion of these entities. Delete
events are already generated for endpoints. For completeness,
create and update notifcations for these entities have also
been implemented.

Partially implements: bp endpoint-policy
Change-Id: I5de15459f5b577955056ecc166b450963e85bbc9

commit_message:
Move Cinder NFS backend driver config in cinder-volume-nfs element

This change aims at moving out of cinder/cinder-volume elements
the bits needed to configure the Cinder NFS backend driver and
as such add the nfs-client element which is a dependency for the
NFS backend driver.

To configure Cinder with a pre-existing NFS share, one has to add
cinder-volume-nfs to the image elements and populate the Heat
template with the NFS shares list as per README files.

Change-Id: I79725a19fc61946f9b0f92a0b54c9b3a440b247a

subject: Move Cinder NFS backend driver config in cinder-volume-nfs element

commit_message:
Move Cinder NFS backend driver config in cinder-volume-nfs element

This change aims at moving out of cinder/cinder-volume elements
the bits needed to configure the Cinder NFS backend driver and
as such add the nfs-client element which is a dependency for the
NFS backend driver.

To configure Cinder with a pre-existing NFS share, one has to add
cinder-volume-nfs to the image elements and populate the Heat
template with the NFS shares list as per README files.

Change-Id: I79725a19fc61946f9b0f92a0b54c9b3a440b247a

commit_message:
Fix agent.prepare() when agents disabled

When use of murano agent is disabled, an exception is raised in
agent.prepare() because the queue doesn't exist as instance state.
This patch turns prepare() into a no-op when the agent's not being used.

Change-Id: I27934d124a7245d6fea524a511607ec42a04f311
Closes-Bug: 1359817

commit_message:
Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages

When a ProcessExecutionError is thrown by processutils.execute(), the
exception may contain information such as password. Upstream
applications that just log the message (as several appear to do) could
inadvertently expose these passwords to a user with read access to the
log files. It is therefore considered prudent to invoke
strutils.mask_password() on the command, stdout and stderr in the
exception. A test case has been added to ensure that all three are
properly masked.

OSSA is aware of this change request.

Originally-Submitted-In: I173dfb865e84eb7dee54a22c76db1e4f125a0a8a

Change-Id: Ie122db5f19802f519b96ed024ab3f2b5eede3eee
Closes-Bug: #1343604

commit_message:
Fixes hyper-v volume attach when host is AD member

The domain name gets added to the initiator name used by the host
if it's an Active Directory member.

Currently the method which gets the initiator name does not take
this into account when retrieving the default initiator name.

Trying to use a wrong initiator name will lead to an exception when
trying to log in to the according iSCSI target.

This patch simply appends the domain name (when the host is an AD
member) to the initiator name used to log in to iSCSI targets.

Closes-Bug: #1328870
(cherry-picked from commit 0d9419f2b36561bf50bbe0f720c8dd8ad4e96660)

Change-Id: Ifbe762c685e46081059a01043431b2c4ac5473fc

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V vm state issue

The method which gets VM related information can fail if the
vm is in an intermediary state such as "Shutting down".
The reason is that some of the Hyper-V specific vm states
are not defined as possible states.

This patch assures that a valid state is always returned by
this method.

Change-Id: I64e95f6b537e83a30dd64474f63f140e0e8e7373
Closes-Bug: #1352428

So the two things I'm aware of that are relevant to this are Ironic and Open Attestation - is it appropriate to insert these into a guide focused on current hardening practices?

We could then update it to something like:

"There are two projects currently affiliated with OpenStack that will allow validation of an image hash before instance launch.

Open Attestation does it this way...<I'll research and fill in as appropriate>

Ironic does it this way...<same as above>

There is still no method for users to upload signatures and images to automatically validate before launch (or modified if covered in Ironic/OA)"

Is that better, or does that still alter the subject/intent?'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-08-19 17:50:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
VMware: remove specific VC support from class VMwareVolumeOps

This support is no longer needed as we only support the VC driver
since commit 1deb31f85a8f5d1e261b2cf1eddc537a5da7f60b.

Change-Id: Iad71fceb580620b1843ce3cf5d926343d8113945

subject: VMware: remove Host class

commit 1deb31f85a8f5d1e261b2cf1eddc537a5da7f60b.

commit_message:
Improved robustness of devstack install script for snapshot

Previously, the devstack install script assumed the
directory congress/etc/snapshot existed.  If it didn't,
the install would fail.

This change checks if the directory exists and
proceeds accordingly.

Change-Id: Ia4dfae34f9946f32b5bf8b35afcfbfc935882972

commit_message:
Allow using non-default collectors

The local collector is not in DEFAULT_COLLECTORS, but should be usable
explicitly. It, however, suffers from a bug where only
DEFAULT_COLLECTORS are allowed through.

Change-Id: Ia42d1acd39638b448e2e2bfa26aff1c7ae415b71

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version.

We use semantic versioning, not pbr's pre-version facility. This
line causes local package builds to have the wrong version, and
pbr will in future detect this and error.

Change-Id: Iff26a28a48a7b14df82df06eb102af539c367c39

Closes-Bug: #1327988
'}]
commit_message:
Disable sshd GSSAPI auth

GSSAPI is not currently implemented in Fuel, so
it only slows incoming SSH connections. Disabling
it will enhance user experience.

Change-Id: I22e808462889a095aa53592d7905279e898006a4
Closes-Bug: #1327988

commit_message:
Don't exit if we are not on a branch

We don't want to exit if we can't pull a branch reference from one
of the tools repositories, which we do as we are running under set -e

collector in os-collect-config, this will not be applied until a

Change-Id: I40e6680ef7f69e8f2319caa7e91cef5529cb3741

commit_message:
Force heat_local collector on seed first boot

Although is configured on the config.json file to only use heat_local
collector in os-collect-config, this will not be applied until a
first os-apply-config execution, so on the first boot of the seed node
it will try to get the metadata from heat and ec2 and wait to them
to timeout.

Change-Id: I40e6680ef7f69e8f2319caa7e91cef5529cb3741

commit_message:
Fixes Nova configuration for utilisation of Qpid for Telemetry

As reported in bug 1331903, without rpc_backend entry, Ceilometer
is unable to collect Qpid statistics. Now fixed for SUSE-based.

Note, this entry should already be put in place as per:
icehouse/install-guide/install/yum/content/nova-compute.html

If this is seen as too much duplication, I'll abandon. However,
without this, things don't work as expected.

Change-Id: Icaf4b3e99c20ddea3edf29dd8888206cb6177c83
Closes-Bug: #1331903

commit_message:
Implement sahara client plugin

Sahara is an integrated project, so python-saharaclient is added
to requirements.txt and saharaclient imports are mandatory.
Also sahara client is added to stevedore configuration.

Change-Id: Ide77975026175dd9d638cb4640925bfd3eade40a
Implements: blueprint sahara-as-heat-resource

'}, {'created': '2014-08-07 13:46:06.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Create VMwareImage object for image metadata

This change pulls the nested function _get_image_properties() out of
spawn() and makes it a factory method for the new VMwareImage object.

Linked clone logic is moved from a separate function in vmops.py to
the new get_image_properties() function.

This has a knock-on effect that vmware.use_linked_clone config option
is now defined and used in driver, and also used vmware_images. driver
has an import chain which imports vmware_images. This creates a
problem using vmware.use_linked_clone as a kwarg default due to the
design of oslo.config. The solution is to ensure driver registers all
its config options before importing any nova modules. An alternative
would have been to move the option to vmware_images, which is its
primary user, and worked around its use in driver. However, this would
have split these config files, and I considered it worse.

vmware_images.get_vmdk_size_and_properties() is no longer used, and is
removed.

Tests have been updated and/or moved as appropriate. No tests have
been removed.

This change has been split out of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/87002/, which was written by Shawn
Hartsock.

commit_message:
VMware: Create VMwareImage object for image metadata

This change pulls the nested function _get_image_properties() out of
spawn() and makes it a factory method for the new VMwareImage object.

Linked clone logic is moved from a separate function in vmops.py to
the new get_image_properties() function.

vmware_images.get_vmdk_size_and_properties() is no longer used, and is
removed.

Tests have been updated and/or moved as appropriate. No tests have
been removed.

This change has been split out of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/87002/, which was written by Shawn
Hartsock.

commit_message:
remove tenant-id from uri

Barbican server will be dropping project-id (a.k.a tenant-id)
from its resource API (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/105562/).
Once that happens, the client will be broken. This commit
fixes that by removing all references of tenant-id from the
secret/order resource URIs. Also, for the unauthenticated use
case, the tenant-id is now passed to the server in the request
header as X-Project-Id

Patch Set 7:
  Rebased and fixed merge issue

Change-Id: I9961e13194485b7945060b18130b4b5265022367
Implements: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/barbican/+spec/api-remove-uri-tenant-id
CR: #1353101

commit_message:
do_not_merge: use oslo.vmware

(Included here a version of review.openstack.org/70175 to enable the use
of oslo.vmware library. Please direct review efforts for the oslo.vmware
integration to review.openstack.org/70175 instead. Once the latter
merges, this patch can be removed and the patch chain on which this
patch resides can be rebased accordingly)

Change-Id: Ie086597a51bfbed3eddb92922ae147b740c59f94

(5 comments)

I think we want this to serve 2 audiences: a developer who is actually running the code and a curious reader who is skipping the commands but wants a feel for the workflow and what congress is all about.   Perhaps we should focus on the curious reader and the exposition they need, while including the commands for the developer.  If we do that, we might want to reorg so that the curious reader quickly gets to the point of seeing what the use case is and how we write policy to address that use case, with install details and OS manipulation coming later.

Also, we should figure out where to include this in the overall docs.  Entry point is index.rst.'}, {'account_id': 12875, 'date': '2014-08-14 18:24:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-14 18:24:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Add a Congress tutorial for group membership

This tutorial illustrates how to create a Congress monitoring policy that
detects when one Openstack tenant shares a network with another
Openstack tenant, and then flags that sharing as a policy violation.

Change-Id: Idb348ffb0723399c2beca3b8001299a7b6a36e13

commit_message:
Updated berkshelf to 3.1.5

Updated berkshelf from 2.0.18 to 3.1.5 in Gemfile and added supermarket
source to Berksfile. Also removed sysctl from berksfile since it was
already removed from metadata in 7.0.2 and is not needed anymore.

Change-Id: I8bc2164f742df808f4f6b0f13b6bc566fafdbde3
Implements: blueprint update-berkshelf

commit_message:
Fixed return value in row_model's get_items

In the non-standard case, row_model's get_items returns before the
end of the function.  Those return values were lists instead of
the dicts required by a recent change.

This change ensures get_items always returns a dict.

Change-Id: Icd2511fc9d73d00268a44dda38542d02fc60fd97

>so the check could be done there instead and then it would apply to all backends.

No it shouldn't dispatcher doesn't know about msg_ids cause it's working on a different level + msg_id is a backend specific field (0MQ should work without it in the future).

Proper fix would be to create separate classes for cast and call messages so dispatcher would use them to determin if reply should be sent. Nice catch, and thanks for the fix. It actually closely mirrors what the legacy rpc code in oslo-incubator does:

 class RpcContext(rpc_common.CommonRpcContext):
     """Context that supports replying to a rpc.call."""
     ...
    def reply(self, ...):
	if self.msg_id:
            msg_reply(self.conf, self.msg_id, self.reply_q, ...)
	    if ending:
	        self.msg_id = None



However, I think we also need a test for this - i.e. one that will fail if we reply() to a message which was sent with send(wait_for_reply=False) and this causes something to be sent to the reply queue. This probably needs to be a new, standalone test case.

Finally, a bug report would also be useful here with more complete details - I don't look for a bug report with every commit like some people do, but this is a pretty important bug and a bug report would be useful for tracking it.

Thanks again.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-11 08:09:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Sorry for being a little late with reply. IMHO this patch does not need a test. Unit test is something that ensures that program behaves like it *should* behave. Positive cases are covered by existing rabbit tests and tempest.

In this particular case you are proposing to write a test to ensure that program doesn't behave as it shouldn't. It almost the same as we would write a test that program doesn't do "rm -rf /". For me this test just makes no sense. I try to imagine how this test will look like:

assertNotCalled(driver.send(...))

Its almost the same as:

assertNotCalled(subprocess.call(['rm -rf /']))

Cause of this I still fail to see how it will help to prevent regressions. We cannot cover all possible situations and it will not prevent us from sending reply to wrong msg_id or any other error."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-08-14 09:44:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

As Mark said earlier: "However, I think we also need a test for this - i.e. one that will fail if we reply() to a message which was sent with send(wait_for_reply=False) and this causes something to be sent to the reply queue."

reply is not sent to reply queue it is sent to default exchange and with no routing key. Cause of this it's just thrown away and we cannot receive it on client side.'}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-08-15 19:53:38.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

As openstack committers we all have same rights and same rules to follow. As reviewers some of us are trusted with rights to decide that patches are good enough to be merged.

However lately I have the feeling that while all developers are equal, some developers are more equal than others (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/107907/ , https://review.openstack.org/#/c/81193/ , https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38339/).
Because of this I'm really frustrated that I'm asked to follow the rules that others do not follow.

As I already said this change does not require a test. Since people here do not agree with me I abandon this change. Have a nice day to all of you :)"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-08-17 15:36:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Alexei, please reconsider. We're trying to raise the standards on all of the Oslo libraries, and that includes writing more tests. In this case, besides catching regressions, a test would help document the expected behavior for new driver authors, which is something we've also been discussing in light of the AMQP 1.0 driver work. When we have a way to write truly functional tests using real broker services, we can do that, but for now a unit test will still be helpful."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-08-17 16:08:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Doug let "M" be an infinite set of all possible actions. Lets assume that "A" is a finite set of actions executed by certain code. In such case set of actions *not* executed by the code is "N" = "M" - "A". It follows from the above that "N" is also an infinite set. 

Action "Sending reply in a case when it should not be sent" belongs to infinite set of "N". I do not understand why we should write tests for such actions cause we'll need infinite number of tests to cover them all. IMHO we should concentrate on functional and performance testing instead.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-08-18 08:17:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I find it counterproductive to link to reviews that lacked unit tests to justify their lack for your patches. There is a clear benefit from the test - to prove that cast does what it intends to do in comparison to call - not sending reply.

I also think that your comment which implies there is some conspiracy among existing contributors directed against you is unfair. I do think people are united here for the common good and made nothing to think otherwise. [Though comments can still be wrong, written in wrong time of day or mood or under influence... :)]

I know it's sometimes frustrating to go thru review cycle here in openstack.

As for performance and functional testing, yeah, we should move there though I don't know any specifics. If we don't, you can start discussion on the matter. Otherwise, join the effort."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-08-18 11:59:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

>I find it counterproductive to link to reviews that lacked unit tests to justify their lack for your patches.

I agree. Let's put all emotions aside. My main reason is that for each patch there is a value that defines if it's good or bad. People here say that value for this patch is negative without the test. I'm ok with this and that's why I abandoned it.

>There is a clear benefit from the test - to prove that cast does what it intends to do in comparison to call - not sending reply.

Please see my previous comment. I think this patch does not need a test, and it is contrary to common sense. Anyone can propose a better patch.

>I also think that your comment which implies there is some conspiracy among existing contributors directed against you is unfair. I do think people are united here for the common good and made nothing to think otherwise. [Though comments can still be wrong, written in wrong time of day or mood or under influence... :)]
I know it's sometimes frustrating to go thru review cycle here in openstack.

I don't think or say that there is some conspiracy among existing contributors directed against me. I say that there are different rules for different people and I don't like it.

>As for performance and functional testing, yeah, we should move there though I don't know any specifics. If we don't, you can start discussion on the matter. Otherwise, join the effort.

Unfortunately we cannot reach consensus even in such a small change. I'm afraid that it's useless for me to propose anything bigger than this. I'm working on functional tests cause I would like to propose an alternative driver implementation for 0MQ (so functional tests are needed to compare it to other drivers). However I think that my implementation will become a fork cause my communication skills are not enough to move it through review process."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-08-18 12:16:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> I agree. Let's put all emotions aside. My main reason is that for each patch there is a value that defines if it's good or bad. People here say that value for this patch is negative without the test. I'm ok with this and that's why I abandoned it.

That's not what -1 means. -1 means that there are some things to be done before the patch is merged. If people would feel that your patch is worthless, they would put -2. Which is not the case.

> I don't think or say that there is some conspiracy among existing contributors directed against me. I say that there are different rules for different people and I don't like it.

But maybe there are no different *rules*; instead, people sometimes forget to request unit tests. I've pushed some patches without unit tests to oslo before, and I would say that it became possible not because I had any special rules just for me, but instead because people didn't pay attention as much as they probably should have done (side note: for some of those patches, I felt guilty enough afterwards to send unit tests separately as follow-ups).

> Unfortunately we cannot reach consensus even in such a small change. I'm afraid that it's useless for me to propose anything bigger than this. I'm working on functional tests cause I would like to propose an alternative driver implementation for 0MQ (so functional tests are needed to compare it to other drivers). However I think that my implementation will become a fork cause my communication skills are not enough to move it through review process.

Of course you're open to fork any of the code. Though in that way you reduce the user's value from it, because probably it won't be shipped by distributions. Instead of thinking about forks in advance, I suggest you to think about collaboration. There is no conflict here, really, and nothing that would stop you from collaborating with oslo team."}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2014-08-18 16:16:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Here is a cherry-pick with pilot version of unit tests for impl_rabbit.py https://review.openstack.org/#/c/115010/

w/o patch: MismatchError: 2 != 0 (_send_reply called 2 times)

w/ patch: No errors (_send_reply called 0 times)

impl_qpid.py is TODO'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-08-18 16:53:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Should not send replies for cast messages

Cast messages will not contain a msg_id  and we're currently
sending messages to the reply_q with empty msg_id. In order
to fix it we should not send replies if there is no msg_id
in message.

Closes-bug: #1355058
Change-Id: I913bdf58aa258e355c5eb14fe3623b10b2876f65

commit_message:
Use rfc3986 library to validate URL paths and URIs

More work needs to be done in rfc3986 to give the user more control over what
they consider to be a valid URI in the context of RFC 3986. For example, a
previous incarnation of these tests checked that "1" and "abc" were invalid
when according to the RFC they are.

Update the API samples and tests to use valid URIs

DocImpact

Change-Id: I288fbaead64990db1053b7a11e82904611b8498f

commit_message:
Implement methods to modify volume metadata.

There are four methods in nova/volume/cinder.py which are
NotImplemented. They are as follows:
  1. get_volume_metadata
  2. delete_volume_metadata
  3. update_volume_metadata
  4. get_volume_metadata_value
These methods are required in cases where nova needs to modify
a cinder volume's metadata, e.g. attach and detach time. It also
completes the cinder.API class.

Change-Id: I360076ae28db43e661466f556425947813c9040e
Closes-Bug: #1296164

commit_message:
Data Processing post-bootstrap 3 UI fixes

Some of the data processing forms were showing extra fields
that should have been hidden.  That was fixed by using
form-group rather than control-group.  Also, the cancel button
was missing its outline on some of the forms because it was
missing the btn-default class.  Other buttons used to choose
libraries and add configs were also missing btn-default.
* Details pages had a large gap, fixed row-fluid --> col-sm-12
* row-fluid --> row in other places per migration guide
* icon-plus/minus --> glyphicon-plus/minus
* select inputs have now have form-control class
* unnecessary margins deleted for "Remove" buttons
* list-style added for node processes <ul>

Co-Authored-By: Nikita Konovalov <nkonovalov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I5f988516290c95e6dba663aa58abeb07563c5bb4
Closes-Bug: #1350372
Closes-Bug: #1352590
Closes-Bug: #1352812

commit_message:
Enable several checks and do not check docs/source/conf.py

* E265 block comment should start with '# '
* H302 import only modules

Do not check docs/source/conf.py. The file is imported from the
cookiecutter template.

Documented why checks are ignored and if they should be enabled
in the future.

Change-Id: I367064ecaa6d1fd9d918f7ce003303e2db660647

if instance.vm_state == vm_states.RESIZED:

will fail because migration status already updated

User is able to do the migration operations when they found erro
so we don't need to handle this kind of error for them

commit_message:
Keep Migration status in automatic confirm-resize

function in compute/manager.py _poll_unconfirmed_resizes
will translate the migrate status from finished to error
whenever finds a problem ,Consider the following case

1) _poll_unconfirmed_resizes runs and founds several migrations to be confirmed
2) user deletes the instance, so its task state will be changed to DELETING
3) _poll_unconfirmed_resizes will find the task state is not None,
it will make the migration error status
4) following code in _delete
if instance.vm_state == vm_states.RESIZED:
self._confirm_resize_on_deleting(context, instance)
will fail because migration status already updated

User is able to do the migration operations when they found error
so we don't need to handle this kind of error for them

Change-Id: Ia79dd56c9c1fa8add7dc138d838cbfbac4523ac3
Closes-Bug: #1301696

commit_message:
Allow selecting the network for doing the ssh with

Previously, nova ssh was searching for network types: public and
private, which seems to be incorrect (fixed and floating seems to be
correct), causing that this command has probably never worked.

This commit fixes the above and adds an option for selecting the network
to use, which is helpful when there are more networks for the VM.

Change-Id: I01ea6cee725c0feaacab60975c3792b0ac1305e9
Closes-Bug: #1227694

commit_message:
Unbundle all JavaScript libraries from Horizon

Remove all external JS libraries from Horizon, and pull them in as
xstatic packages instead.

Bootstrap, jquery-ui and jquery.bootstrap.wizard will be unbundled in separate
patches, as there are some problems adding them to global-requirements.

Partial-Implements: blueprint remove-javascript-bundling
Change-Id: Icbbcf8e58db2dcce96d187f7307201f728812cd2

Add ensure_package class

This class ensures installation or upgrade/downgrade
of several important libraries and packages that
was not manages by Puppet before.

commit_message:
Fix dvr router getting scheduled on router update

This commit will fix the issue where in DVR mode, router update command
creates router namespaces on nodes, even if there are no VMs hosted on
them for the attached subnet.

Closes-bug: 1353266

Change-Id: I4252515a40eda3ed089be7fdf3fc6910121d2971

commit_message:
Add database charset during create

When using MySQL, the database charset should be utf-8.

And the default charset is latin1, which will cause glance db sync
failed.

Closes-bug: #1356887
Change-Id: I50e299410de8068150d1c405994ecb96918fbc7d

commit_message:
Fixed oslotest version pin

It turned out that pip is too smart and knows that 1.1.0.0a1 is less
than 1.1.0. We have 1.1.0.0a1 on PyPI for now, so we need to require
that specific version until the final release is available.

Change-Id: I23d85cf1237177561955df05c752871c443e3630

Rename range to avoid shadowing the builtin

This refactor supports a patch I was reviewing [1].  I thought it
better to apply this consistently in this file as a separate refactor
so that that patch could be done cleaner.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100963

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-20 14:39:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-21 09:53:33.000000000', 'message': "Upgrades, fix for repo path for host system upgrader

* in 5.0.1 to run host system upgrader
  we used repository which was in upgrade
  tar ball, after upgrade user could delete
  the repo with all temporary data, as
  result user can get broken repository
  which leads to the error during puppet
  run, add hook to fix repo path for 5.0.1
  version
* copy directory with centos repository
  on host system upgrade stage, it helps
  to keep our engines separated from each
  other and user won't have problems with
  removed repository

Closes-bug: #1358686
Change-Id: Iba8897322af471aa9cd0babed4ff18f31ba8ca9d
"}]
commit_message:
Upgrades, fix for repo path for host system upgrader

* in 5.0.1 to run host system upgrader
  we used repository which was in upgrade
  tar ball, after upgrade user could delete
  the repo with all temporary data, as
  result user can get broken repository
  which leads to the error during puppet
  run, add hook to fix repo path for 5.0.1
  version
* copy directory with centos repository
  on host system upgrade stage, it helps
  to keep our engines separated from each
  other and user won't have problems with
  removed repository

Closes-bug: #1358686
Change-Id: Iba8897322af471aa9cd0babed4ff18f31ba8ca9d

This change appears to be good in that it provides us a mechanism to parametrize the size of instances for different data stores. 

The change is being necessitated by the fact that the default image we are creating for cassandra is too 'fat'.

While I like the ability to parametrize the instance sizes, I'd rather we fix the real problem; make the default JVM require less memory. Configure Cassandra to use less memory.

We won't need to bump instance sizes in that case.

I'm marking this change as -1 not because this code is 'bad'. As a matter of fact, I had to do something similar in testing a change for rsync and cassandra startup. But once I knew what was wrong with the jvm size it was apparent that the right fix was to fix the image that we're building for cassandra.

No, I didn't follow through and do that (sorry)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-11 17:24:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

Amrith, you are completely wrong, with less memory cassandra can randomly die because if attempt to use more memory that it can.
Just letting you know - cassandra got perfect mechanisms of memory allocation and you can't tune upstart scripts since you had to have too much knowledge about cassandra in general.

And finally, all integration tests are working on too(i mean too small) flavors like the biggest of them is 756 RAM and if you read cassandra deployment docs(i bet you didn't) you'll find that cassadra requires AT LEAST (!!!) 4GB RAM for successful running.

So, please, find a better arguments and reasons for -1."}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-07-11 20:40:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Even more, just letting you know, there's a possibility that while attempting to run cassandra on 1Gb RAM - each request from clients (mostly bulk writes) can kill Cassandra with java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space"}, {'account_id': 5293, 'date': '2014-07-11 21:50:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Denis: It is completely inappropriate to launch into ad-hominem attacks when reviewing code. Let's be respectful to all members of the community, and promote a culture of collaboration. Saying things like "You are completely wrong", and "I bet you didn't" (read the cassandra deployment docs) are completely unacceptable. Please limit code reviews to critiquing the code at hand -- and be respectful to all members of the community.'}, {'account_id': 1925, 'date': '2014-07-11 22:35:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I would like to echo everything Nikhil stated.  Also please read http://www.openstack.org/legal/community-code-of-conduct/ -- let's be respectful of each other and help better the community."}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-08-21 14:16:29.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Use flavor settings per datastore in int-tests

Reasons:
 - default flavors are not suitable for different datastores,
   such as cassandra.

Changes:
 - parametrizing test_begin.conf to expect flavor refs;

Change-Id: I3d068718a935132ea1637e99468a686ee85422f5
Closes-Bug: #1329310

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version

Generally everything other than the API servers use semantic versioning, not
pbr's pre-version facility. This line causes local package builds to have the
wrong version today, and pbr will in future detect this and error.

Change-Id: Iafd64f79f6c10786db43a7a22beee7b58cd6b78e

Commit a507d42cf5d9912c2b3622e84afb8b7d3278595b makes the
doc builds fail on warnings, so people are probably going
to be running 'tox -e docs' more often. To run that you
need the graphviz package from the distro, so add it to

commit_message:
Add graphviz to list of distro packages to install

Commit a507d42cf5d9912c2b3622e84afb8b7d3278595b makes the
doc builds fail on warnings, so people are probably going
to be running 'tox -e docs' more often. To run that you
need the graphviz package from the distro, so add it to
the list of packages needed when setting up a development
environment.

Change-Id: I47ffe63fddfbbd73c3fc698490ad07235caaf459
Closes-Bug: #1356983

commit_message:
Send quantum_settings:L2:provider as 'nsx'

* Remove alternation of quantum_settings:server:core_plugin
* Send quantum_settings:L2:provider = nsx instead
* Fix Nailgun integration tests

Change-Id: If581b39c0e82f07a0e1a0f8ee9db7da7a6151fe0
Closes-bug: #1358255

Now there is only one system test that run OSTF Heat tests on simple cluster with
Neutron GRE.
Test that run tests on simple cluster with Nova network and test that run test
on cluster with HA mode were added. We need to run OSTF tests in different network

Change-Id: Id41401be81f198037044b76f6bf9ff0a5e023c67

commit_message:
Add two system tests for Heat

Now there is only one system test that run OSTF Heat tests on simple cluster with
Neutron GRE.
Test that run tests on simple cluster with Nova network and test that run test
on cluster with HA mode were added. We need to run OSTF tests in different network
configuration because Heat use different templates for them.

Implements blueprint: add-more-heat-system-tests

Change-Id: Id41401be81f198037044b76f6bf9ff0a5e023c67
